[SPEAKER_15]: And we had proposed, I'm not sure it made it into the changes, we proposed the step back at five stories and above.

550
00:58:21,616 --> 00:58:23,437
[SPEAKER_15]: So that's one of the reasons you're seeing it there.

551
00:58:23,997 --> 00:58:33,421
[SPEAKER_15]: And then the other thing is, and I also think that we did not have this in the zoning, we had recommended that North Street be limited to five stories.

552
00:58:35,022 --> 00:58:37,103
[SPEAKER_15]: So that might be some of the confusion that's going on there.

553
00:58:37,583 --> 00:58:37,783
[SPEAKER_15]: Yep.

554
00:58:44,026 --> 00:58:44,186
[SPEAKER_15]: Yep.

555
00:58:45,327 --> 00:58:47,648
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other scenarios people would like to receive?

556
00:58:48,489 --> 00:58:56,531
[SPEAKER_27]: I not the scenario, but just for clarification that people that are watching the understanding that February and June would be the most impacted months.

557
00:58:57,211 --> 00:59:00,052
[SPEAKER_27]: Or is that just to inform everybody that?

558
00:59:00,652 --> 00:59:01,353
[SPEAKER_15]: Yes, counselor.

559
00:59:01,413 --> 00:59:01,813
[SPEAKER_15]: Absolutely.

560
00:59:01,833 --> 00:59:03,293
[SPEAKER_15]: Why we chose February and June.

561
00:59:03,633 --> 00:59:07,034
[SPEAKER_15]: Those were the dates for the daylight standards in the.

562
00:59:07,534 --> 00:59:10,515
[SPEAKER_15]: So what we wanted to do is given that the

563
00:59:11,455 --> 00:59:16,799
[SPEAKER_15]: Once the daylight standards were passed, the February 21st and June 21st were within those standards.

564
00:59:17,200 --> 00:59:21,363
[SPEAKER_15]: We wanted to make sure we also showed what it looked like during those same dates.

565
00:59:21,443 --> 00:59:22,764
[SPEAKER_15]: So there would be consistency.

566
00:59:23,244 --> 00:59:24,225
[SPEAKER_15]: So thank you for asking that.

567
00:59:24,245 --> 00:59:25,346
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you for the clarification.

568
00:59:25,366 --> 00:59:26,347
[SPEAKER_27]: That's good.

569
00:59:27,247 --> 00:59:28,768
[SPEAKER_27]: It's good to hear the five stories.

570
00:59:29,309 --> 00:59:30,770
[SPEAKER_27]: That's impressive.

571
00:59:30,850 --> 00:59:31,210
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

572
00:59:31,550 --> 00:59:34,613
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

573
00:59:34,673 --> 00:59:37,275
[SPEAKER_08]: Do we have any further clarifying questions from members of the council?

574
00:59:39,682 --> 00:59:43,383
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll turn it over to Chair Carr for clarifying questions and then we'll go to public comments.

575
00:59:45,604 --> 00:59:46,265
[SPEAKER_22]: Okay.

576
00:59:46,765 --> 00:59:53,187
[SPEAKER_22]: Would anyone on the City Board like to make a clarifying question to Emily based on the presentation we just saw?

577
00:59:57,609 --> 00:59:58,209
[SPEAKER_22]: Don't see anything.

578
00:59:58,769 --> 00:59:59,430
[SPEAKER_22]: Are we online?

579
00:59:59,590 --> 01:00:01,971
[SPEAKER_22]: Do you have any comments or questions, clarifying questions?

580
01:00:03,211 --> 01:00:04,231
[SPEAKER_20]: Not at this time, thank you.

581
01:00:04,251 --> 01:00:05,632
[SPEAKER_22]: Okay.

582
01:00:07,923 --> 01:00:11,721
[SPEAKER_22]: I just have one minor one I think it's worth mentioning that.

583
01:00:14,951 --> 01:00:20,595
[SPEAKER_22]: Not every existing building that could be rezoned was shown as new building, right?

584
01:00:20,635 --> 01:00:23,717
[SPEAKER_22]: We just chose a portion of it.

585
01:00:23,737 --> 01:00:34,905
[SPEAKER_22]: I think it's worth just explaining the logic that there's actually, it could be more, but you chose, just to be an example, that you chose certain areas of all three zones that you went for.

586
01:00:34,925 --> 01:00:38,808
[SPEAKER_22]: If you could just elaborate on that for the folks who are listening.

587
01:00:39,320 --> 01:00:40,561
[SPEAKER_15]: Yes, absolutely, I'd be happy to.

588
01:00:40,621 --> 01:01:04,639
[SPEAKER_15]: So we did sort of a quick susceptibility to change analysis, and what that means is under the zoning, it's a combination of what we think might be more possible to change, but also, as I mentioned with the caveats earlier, those that had the right dimensional standards to modify a mixed use building, or a model of mixed use building.

589
01:01:05,119 --> 01:01:06,520
[SPEAKER_15]: So a couple of things that go into that.

590
01:01:06,780 --> 01:01:12,963
[SPEAKER_15]: One is the way the zoning is set up, it's achieving a couple of goals.

591
01:01:13,143 --> 01:01:15,904
[SPEAKER_15]: One is just simply reducing the number of nonconformities.

592
01:01:16,604 --> 01:01:19,786
[SPEAKER_15]: One is allowing a wider variety of uses.

593
01:01:20,446 --> 01:01:23,888
[SPEAKER_15]: Both of those don't require any new developments.

594
01:01:23,928 --> 01:01:24,388
[SPEAKER_15]: There's no.

595
01:01:24,488 --> 01:01:28,390
[SPEAKER_15]: But then the third thing is whether or not there would be new developments now.

596
01:01:29,010 --> 01:01:37,856
[SPEAKER_15]: These are mixed-use districts, but within those mixed-use districts that could allow a residential building, a commercial building, or a mixed-use building.

597
01:01:38,296 --> 01:01:48,343
[SPEAKER_15]: But the mixed-use building has certain characteristics that make it useful for a fit study, a site model like this, and that is a higher ground floor,

598
01:01:49,424 --> 01:01:56,090
[SPEAKER_15]: the requirement to have a certain width of the building that wouldn't be necessarily required for, say, a straight commercial building.

599
01:01:56,471 --> 01:01:58,433
[SPEAKER_15]: So they make it useful for FITS studies.

600
01:01:58,513 --> 01:02:07,202
[SPEAKER_15]: So if we're going to do a FITS study for a mixed-use building, we need to understand which parcels could accommodate a mixed-use building.

601
01:02:07,222 --> 01:02:10,425
[SPEAKER_15]: That's why I was talking about choosing those that have the right depth.

602
01:02:11,666 --> 01:02:22,113
[SPEAKER_15]: So in each case, we looked, or in each of these areas, we wanted to see where there might be a parcel assembly that would be useful for a FIT study.

603
01:02:22,133 --> 01:02:34,161
[SPEAKER_15]: And by parcel assembly, I mean we're taking several parcels in order to fit this model on there, where there might be a vacant lot or an existing use.

604
01:02:34,621 --> 01:02:39,564
[SPEAKER_15]: For example, we looked at a lot of the one-story buildings and said, okay, if you're going to allow

605
01:02:40,665 --> 01:02:42,066
[SPEAKER_15]: more than one story.

606
01:02:42,086 --> 01:02:47,107
[SPEAKER_15]: It's probably going to be a one story that could possibly be useful for modeling.

607
01:02:47,227 --> 01:02:55,831
[SPEAKER_15]: So it was a combination of what's on the ground now, whether or not that parcel depth or width could work, and then could we just

608
01:02:57,071 --> 01:03:02,216
[SPEAKER_15]: look at what happens if you add a couple of parcels together to allow for that sort of development.

609
01:03:02,236 --> 01:03:12,464
[SPEAKER_15]: A couple of the other things that we considered was ownership levels, whether or not, for example, a building had already been recently built.

610
01:03:12,604 --> 01:03:18,610
[SPEAKER_15]: So, for example, BA2, there's some fairly recent residential buildings on industrial parcels.

611
01:03:19,310 --> 01:03:26,811
[SPEAKER_15]: That's not likely to change, but the other industrial parcels in that area that hadn't been built upon, maybe they could.

612
01:03:27,732 --> 01:03:29,592
[SPEAKER_15]: And then some of it, for example, the two St.

613
01:03:29,632 --> 01:03:44,275
[SPEAKER_15]: Clements properties, what we did was we modeled the existing footprint and just increased, so basically the building that is there now, the two buildings that are there now, and just added stories on top of them to see what that would look like.

614
01:03:45,395 --> 01:03:52,682
[SPEAKER_15]: In no case are we suggesting that any of these parcels would be developed the way they're shown here.

615
01:03:52,842 --> 01:03:58,948
[SPEAKER_15]: It's merely for illustrative purposes to understand what the height could look like and what the shadow study could look like.

616
01:04:01,370 --> 01:04:01,630
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you.

617
01:04:01,650 --> 01:04:02,291
[SPEAKER_22]: That's very helpful.

618
01:04:02,371 --> 01:04:07,576
[SPEAKER_22]: I guess the only other question I had was the historic buildings around St.

619
01:04:07,616 --> 01:04:09,217
[SPEAKER_22]: Clements, the two schools.

620
01:04:11,250 --> 01:04:24,695
[SPEAKER_22]: whether it's any of the three versions of the BA2 that you modeled, if they're all significantly more than those buildings, is there any incentive to save those buildings?

621
01:04:24,795 --> 01:04:28,197
[SPEAKER_22]: Because some of them go up to, I think, seven stories, right?

622
01:04:28,217 --> 01:04:31,578
[SPEAKER_22]: So there are quite a lot of potential new real estate.

623
01:04:31,918 --> 01:04:36,120
[SPEAKER_22]: How would there be any incentive to save that building if you could build so much

624
01:04:36,940 --> 01:04:47,373
[SPEAKER_22]: by just getting rid of it, because if we did this in Memphis Square, we try to incentivize by limiting the height, and then say you can build more, because we started with a lower number, I think.

625
01:04:47,834 --> 01:04:51,018
[SPEAKER_22]: I guess I'm not seeing the same approach here, or maybe I'm not reading it correctly.

626
01:04:51,641 --> 01:04:53,663
[SPEAKER_15]: I think for the two St.

627
01:04:53,703 --> 01:05:08,636
[SPEAKER_15]: Clements buildings that we modeled, we had not had those in our original boundary, so we modeled them according to your suggestion to add them and to see what they would look like at those different heights.

628
01:05:09,777 --> 01:05:15,642
[SPEAKER_15]: I think we kept the same incentives for historic buildings in this zoning as we did for Medford Square.

629
01:05:16,583 --> 01:05:20,486
[SPEAKER_15]: the same ability to do the historic conversion as we did for Medford Square.

630
01:05:20,887 --> 01:05:24,690
[SPEAKER_15]: But the reason we modeled them was essentially at your request.

631
01:05:25,011 --> 01:05:30,076
[SPEAKER_15]: So we are not making a prediction one way or the other as to how they might develop.

632
01:05:30,536 --> 01:05:31,757
[SPEAKER_15]: I will say that

633
01:05:33,679 --> 01:05:35,660
[SPEAKER_15]: They are existing three-story buildings.

634
01:05:39,862 --> 01:05:48,467
[SPEAKER_15]: You would know better than I as an architect how those buildings could add stories on top of them, the type of structural reinforcement that might be necessary.

635
01:05:48,828 --> 01:05:59,674
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm making an assumption that they weren't built to be able to support additional stories, so that might be one thing to consider, but those were not originally within the boundaries.

636
01:06:00,833 --> 01:06:01,373
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you very much.

637
01:06:01,393 --> 01:06:01,453
[SPEAKER_22]: Yep.

638
01:06:02,133 --> 01:06:03,054
[SPEAKER_22]: All set on this.

639
01:06:05,375 --> 01:06:05,615
[SPEAKER_08]: Great.

640
01:06:07,775 --> 01:06:12,757
[SPEAKER_08]: If there's no further clarifying questions, and I'm seeing none, we will go to open the public hearing.

641
01:06:14,178 --> 01:06:19,359
[SPEAKER_08]: So for the public hearing, we will take folks here in person at the podium or on Zoom.

642
01:06:19,379 --> 01:06:21,560
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll alternate between in person and on Zoom.

643
01:06:22,000 --> 01:06:23,141
[SPEAKER_08]: You will have three minutes.

644
01:06:23,441 --> 01:06:27,302
[SPEAKER_08]: You can share your name and your city or neighborhood for the record before you speak.

645
01:06:28,234 --> 01:06:30,435
[SPEAKER_08]: and we will go from there.

646
01:06:30,535 --> 01:06:45,520
[SPEAKER_08]: So if you would like to comment on the proposals as well as, you know, the presentation and kind of the decisions that we are going to be looking at tonight, please come to line up behind the microphone here in the chambers or raise your hands on Zoom.

647
01:06:45,540 --> 01:06:53,823
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, we'll start at the podium.

648
01:06:54,123 --> 01:06:55,064
[SPEAKER_08]: If you could provide

649
01:06:56,182 --> 01:06:58,225
[SPEAKER_08]: your name and your city or neighborhood.

650
01:06:58,245 --> 01:07:02,151
[SPEAKER_08]: And you're gonna have a little more than three minutes because I gotta get the timer going.

651
01:07:02,191 --> 01:07:03,533
[SPEAKER_08]: So take the extra time.

652
01:07:04,235 --> 01:07:04,895
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you very much.

653
01:07:05,115 --> 01:07:06,035
[SPEAKER_00]: My name is Nick Jorleo.

654
01:07:06,055 --> 01:07:08,336
[SPEAKER_00]: I live in West Medford, 40 Robinson Road.

655
01:07:09,756 --> 01:07:14,217
[SPEAKER_00]: I generally support spending more time with getting the use table right on the zoning.

656
01:07:15,078 --> 01:07:21,019
[SPEAKER_00]: Generally, I would say I support discretionary permit requirements for uses that would be more controversial to the community.

657
01:07:21,179 --> 01:07:23,860
[SPEAKER_00]: So for example, larger housing projects.

658
01:07:24,740 --> 01:07:27,020
[SPEAKER_00]: I look at the multiple dwelling use, for example.

659
01:07:27,320 --> 01:07:31,701
[SPEAKER_00]: Under the current draft, it allows for six or more unit structures as of right in all three sub-districts.

660
01:07:32,182 --> 01:07:33,662
[SPEAKER_00]: I think that should require a special permit.

661
01:07:34,562 --> 01:07:36,964
[SPEAKER_00]: Another good example of this would be the neighborhood medical office.

662
01:07:37,004 --> 01:07:46,430
[SPEAKER_00]: I know you all voted on that at the last meeting, but I'd recommend a special permit in all three sub-districts for that one as well, just given the issues with the vagueness of the definition.

663
01:07:46,450 --> 01:07:53,495
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think one thing to keep in mind is when you're allowing a use as of right, you're taking away community discretion.

664
01:07:53,535 --> 01:07:58,258
[SPEAKER_00]: You're saying developer can go to the building department, get their permit, and be on their way with their project.

665
01:07:58,478 --> 01:07:59,419
[SPEAKER_00]: The community discretion

666
01:08:00,690 --> 01:08:04,974
[SPEAKER_00]: aspect of this allows for residents have a say in what their neighborhood look like.

667
01:08:05,014 --> 01:08:07,976
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think generally that's what we should be thinking about when we're looking at zoning.

668
01:08:08,897 --> 01:08:12,739
[SPEAKER_00]: I'd also say with the use table there's some unreasonable restrictions that I see.

669
01:08:13,380 --> 01:08:15,662
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm looking at the motor vehicle uses for example.

670
01:08:15,742 --> 01:08:17,143
[SPEAKER_00]: You know why are they all not allowed.

671
01:08:18,083 --> 01:08:21,345
[SPEAKER_00]: I know, you know, people have said this before me, but yes, people have cars.

672
01:08:21,485 --> 01:08:22,085
[SPEAKER_00]: It's a reality.

673
01:08:22,105 --> 01:08:24,226
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, they need them to get place to place.

674
01:08:24,946 --> 01:08:31,489
[SPEAKER_00]: So as much as it'd be nice to walk, I mean, it'd be great to have a place to like fill your gas tank up or to get your car repaired.

675
01:08:31,809 --> 01:08:33,390
[SPEAKER_00]: So why aren't we allowing those uses?

676
01:08:34,430 --> 01:08:36,231
[SPEAKER_00]: And also just generally blue collar uses.

677
01:08:36,291 --> 01:08:37,551
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, why are we restricting those?

678
01:08:37,771 --> 01:08:44,394
[SPEAKER_00]: I think blue collar uses are great for the fabric of the community, certainly for the tax base, but also just for the character of a neighborhood.

679
01:08:44,554 --> 01:08:46,615
[SPEAKER_00]: So let's consider allowing those as well.

680
01:08:47,909 --> 01:08:58,176
[SPEAKER_00]: With the dormitory fraternity use, you know, I wonder why actually it's even in the zoning to begin with, because I'm thinking that TOPS will just make a Dover Amendment argument if they want to build a frat or sorority.

681
01:08:58,616 --> 01:09:05,461
[SPEAKER_00]: They might be able to somehow twist their way into saying this is an educational use, even though we all know what goes on in fraternities and sororities.

682
01:09:05,821 --> 01:09:07,763
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think that'd certainly be debatable.

683
01:09:09,348 --> 01:09:12,209
[SPEAKER_00]: Finally, as for the heights, I know that's kind of the focus of tonight's meeting.

684
01:09:12,329 --> 01:09:13,749
[SPEAKER_00]: I'd say we've gone a little too high.

685
01:09:14,270 --> 01:09:16,230
[SPEAKER_00]: I especially think this is true in BA3, 6 to 8.

686
01:09:16,730 --> 01:09:18,831
[SPEAKER_00]: I think it's far too much for the neighborhood.

687
01:09:19,771 --> 01:09:23,812
[SPEAKER_00]: I know this wasn't even an option considered, but I'd go even lower than the options that were presented to you.

688
01:09:23,832 --> 01:09:25,073
[SPEAKER_00]: I'd go 4 plus 1 on that.

689
01:09:26,053 --> 01:09:33,615
[SPEAKER_00]: I'd like to see a neighborhood that really isn't overcrowded, that really does preserve the quality of life for residents of the hillside.

690
01:09:34,382 --> 01:09:44,310
[SPEAKER_00]: And yes, I understand the goal for many of you is to increase density, but we do have to be realistic in a lot of ways about things like traffic and just quality of life, health.

691
01:09:44,791 --> 01:09:46,192
[SPEAKER_00]: There's a lot of different things to think about.

692
01:09:46,212 --> 01:09:48,574
[SPEAKER_00]: So I hope you'll take the time and make those considerations.

693
01:09:49,314 --> 01:09:55,099
[SPEAKER_00]: A lot of these technical suggestions I laid out for all of you in a letter, which I submitted as a public comment in writing.

694
01:09:55,599 --> 01:09:55,900
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

695
01:09:58,101 --> 01:09:58,422
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

696
01:09:59,718 --> 01:10:03,200
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, gonna go next to Chris Bennett on Zoom.

697
01:10:03,260 --> 01:10:07,883
[SPEAKER_08]: Chris, if you could give your name and city or neighborhood for the record.

698
01:10:08,924 --> 01:10:10,365
[SPEAKER_08]: And you'll have three minutes.

699
01:10:11,806 --> 01:10:13,207
[SPEAKER_12]: Hi, my name is Chris Bennett.

700
01:10:13,627 --> 01:10:15,148
[SPEAKER_12]: I live on Martin Street in Medford.

701
01:10:16,549 --> 01:10:18,290
[SPEAKER_12]: I am a member of the Hillside community.

702
01:10:19,111 --> 01:10:23,334
[SPEAKER_12]: I have a couple of questions specifically related to how this is presented.

703
01:10:24,074 --> 01:10:24,975
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm not an architect.

704
01:10:26,094 --> 01:10:27,555
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm a special education advocate.

705
01:10:28,716 --> 01:10:35,961
[SPEAKER_12]: I also have a good basis in medical terminology, but when we're talking about architecture, it's not my game.

706
01:10:36,862 --> 01:10:47,830
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm having an issue when I'm trying to look at some of the schematics that are being shown without street signs or street names for me, because it's very hard for me to picture it.

707
01:10:48,071 --> 01:10:50,592
[SPEAKER_12]: I can't think that way.

708
01:10:51,493 --> 01:10:54,995
[SPEAKER_12]: So I would like to see this is Winthrop Street.

709
01:10:55,095 --> 01:11:02,179
[SPEAKER_12]: This is, you know, whatever side street that is that you go down off across from North Street.

710
01:11:03,960 --> 01:11:06,602
[SPEAKER_12]: But my major concern is the height that we're talking about.

711
01:11:07,562 --> 01:11:17,167
[SPEAKER_12]: And when I was listening, why are we doing these kind of things that we why are we keeping it a height limit like because of Medford Square?

712
01:11:17,187 --> 01:11:17,648
[SPEAKER_12]: And I'm thinking,

713
01:11:18,928 --> 01:11:22,691
[SPEAKER_12]: That's like comparing apples to oranges because this is like a community area here.

714
01:11:23,151 --> 01:11:29,215
[SPEAKER_12]: I mean, you have certain places down on Boston Ave, but you have a lot of homes too.

715
01:11:29,636 --> 01:11:32,317
[SPEAKER_12]: You have a lot of three-family homes, you have a lot of two-family homes.

716
01:11:33,138 --> 01:11:41,764
[SPEAKER_12]: But the final thing that I wanted to ask about was why we're talking seven stories in that little area there.

717
01:11:42,605 --> 01:11:44,185
[SPEAKER_12]: That really concerns me.

718
01:11:44,246 --> 01:11:44,746
[SPEAKER_12]: We don't know.

719
01:11:44,846 --> 01:11:46,726
[SPEAKER_12]: We've already put up a huge dormitory.

720
01:11:47,506 --> 01:11:50,767
[SPEAKER_12]: That's impacted my drivability for a long time.

721
01:11:52,008 --> 01:11:56,569
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm talking about going in the opposite direction now toward West Medford Square.

722
01:11:57,269 --> 01:11:59,310
[SPEAKER_12]: I try to avoid going through Medford Square.

723
01:11:59,510 --> 01:12:01,171
[SPEAKER_12]: I usually use Boston Ave all the time.

724
01:12:01,711 --> 01:12:08,053
[SPEAKER_12]: And I'm just, I see the traffic that hits there now, and I'm just overly, like, seriously concerned about that.

725
01:12:09,033 --> 01:12:09,373
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

726
01:12:11,914 --> 01:12:12,274
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

727
01:12:14,293 --> 01:12:19,135
[SPEAKER_08]: We will go back to the podium, if you could give your name and your neighborhood for the record, and you'll have three minutes.

728
01:12:19,576 --> 01:12:19,836
[SPEAKER_31]: Sure.

729
01:12:20,296 --> 01:12:21,597
[SPEAKER_31]: My name is Kristen Lugowski.

730
01:12:21,657 --> 01:12:23,177
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm in Medford Hillside also.

731
01:12:23,197 --> 01:12:27,800
[SPEAKER_31]: I think in general, having mixed use is a good thing.

732
01:12:28,260 --> 01:12:35,283
[SPEAKER_31]: Obviously, we need more housing, and we could use some more businesses around to help get the neighborhoods, you know, vibrant.

733
01:12:35,303 --> 01:12:38,445
[SPEAKER_31]: You know, Medford could use a little bit more going on.

734
01:12:39,606 --> 01:12:42,627
[SPEAKER_31]: My main concerns again like Chris I think are some of the height things.

735
01:12:42,647 --> 01:12:47,731
[SPEAKER_31]: You know I want it still feel like a neighborhood when we have mixed use.

736
01:12:47,891 --> 01:12:51,033
[SPEAKER_31]: And again I do want to see more housing for people that they can afford to.

737
01:12:51,553 --> 01:12:57,677
[SPEAKER_31]: But the B3 really concerns me because I was looking at the shadows and it did definitely clip some of those.

738
01:12:58,417 --> 01:13:02,638
[SPEAKER_31]: you know, residential houses in both February and in the summer, right?

739
01:13:02,818 --> 01:13:07,700
[SPEAKER_31]: So I would not want to be in one of those houses and lose the little bit of sunlight I get every day.

740
01:13:08,260 --> 01:13:17,263
[SPEAKER_31]: So I would, the other thing that concerns me about that is the way the houses, maybe it's just the modeling, but right now those buildings that were there or are there are pretty offset from North Street.

741
01:13:17,763 --> 01:13:19,544
[SPEAKER_31]: And the modeling, it had it right up against the road.

742
01:13:19,564 --> 01:13:22,065
[SPEAKER_31]: So maybe that's part of the issue for that shadow.

743
01:13:23,086 --> 01:13:39,401
[SPEAKER_31]: The other thing I'd like to see, if you guys ever do more modeling on the shadowing, is to see what it looks like for when the sun's coming east, because it was really hard to tell with the houses on the other side of Boston Ave towards the university how that shadow would impact them.

744
01:13:40,102 --> 01:13:43,264
[SPEAKER_31]: really easy to see what the shadow towards the railroad track looks like.

745
01:13:43,284 --> 01:13:52,348
[SPEAKER_31]: But you couldn't really see how those other people on the other side were impacted because the east facing sun comes in that way and they would be eclipsed by some of those houses probably.

746
01:13:52,368 --> 01:13:55,910
[SPEAKER_31]: And again it's just the way the view of that modeling happens.

747
01:13:55,970 --> 01:14:01,233
[SPEAKER_31]: It's really hard to tell how when the sun's rising that impacts those houses behind those buildings.

748
01:14:02,294 --> 01:14:05,797
[SPEAKER_31]: So I think that would just be something to take into consideration when you're doing this.

749
01:14:05,837 --> 01:14:12,162
[SPEAKER_31]: It doesn't impact me directly, but I just, I walk through those neighborhoods all the time with my dog, so I'm very familiar with the area.

750
01:14:13,764 --> 01:14:23,772
[SPEAKER_31]: But it's just those kind of little things, just again, great to have more mixed use, great to have more housing, but again, just thinking about the impact to the neighborhood directly.

751
01:14:23,792 --> 01:14:27,095
[SPEAKER_31]: The other thing too with the student housing, every student,

752
01:14:28,206 --> 01:14:32,089
[SPEAKER_31]: unit gets one car, we don't even do that for affordable housing.

753
01:14:33,169 --> 01:14:34,830
[SPEAKER_31]: There's a lot of good public transportation.

754
01:14:34,890 --> 01:14:36,011
[SPEAKER_31]: Does everybody need a car?

755
01:14:36,531 --> 01:14:37,192
[SPEAKER_31]: I mean, I have one.

756
01:14:37,452 --> 01:14:39,774
[SPEAKER_31]: I'm privileged, but I also have a house with a driveway.

757
01:14:40,534 --> 01:14:43,396
[SPEAKER_31]: A lot of the people who live off of Boston Ave don't have parking.

758
01:14:43,676 --> 01:14:52,642
[SPEAKER_31]: So I know you're trying not to take away from their parking, but it also is just why do we have all this public transportation if we're just going to assume everybody needs a car?

759
01:14:52,882 --> 01:14:54,783
[SPEAKER_31]: So just some other things to think about.

760
01:14:54,803 --> 01:14:55,944
[SPEAKER_31]: So that's it.

761
01:14:56,324 --> 01:14:56,545
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you.

762
01:14:58,240 --> 01:14:58,740
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

763
01:14:59,821 --> 01:15:01,281
[SPEAKER_08]: We will go back to Zoom.

764
01:15:01,642 --> 01:15:03,843
[SPEAKER_08]: We will go to Laura Longsworth on Zoom.

765
01:15:03,883 --> 01:15:10,786
[SPEAKER_08]: And if there's anyone else in the chamber who does plan to speak, if you could just raise your hand or come to the podium, just so I'm aware.

766
01:15:11,426 --> 01:15:13,627
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll go to Laura Longsworth on Zoom.

767
01:15:16,449 --> 01:15:18,950
[SPEAKER_08]: Laura, if you could write your name and your neighborhood, and you'll have three minutes.

768
01:15:20,251 --> 01:15:20,631
[SPEAKER_33]: Hi there.

769
01:15:21,331 --> 01:15:22,231
[SPEAKER_33]: Laura Longsworth.

770
01:15:22,292 --> 01:15:24,433
[SPEAKER_33]: I live on North Street in Hillside.

771
01:15:26,566 --> 01:15:35,092
[SPEAKER_33]: I thought a lot about the student dorm and I just really would prefer that we didn't go this direction.

772
01:15:35,112 --> 01:15:43,818
[SPEAKER_33]: I think it's kind of building a monoculture in an area where I would love to see just regular housing built.

773
01:15:44,359 --> 01:15:49,362
[SPEAKER_33]: I do think that inviting a concentration of students into that neighborhood is

774
01:15:50,663 --> 01:15:52,846
[SPEAKER_33]: probably not great, not great for the neighborhood.

775
01:15:52,886 --> 01:16:05,801
[SPEAKER_33]: It kind of creates an anchor situation where you have a dorm at one end, a Tufts at the other end, and some of the conversation is about bringing students out of Hillside, and I just think it instead is going to do the opposite.

776
01:16:05,841 --> 01:16:08,864
[SPEAKER_33]: It's just going to create kind of a belt of students

777
01:16:10,354 --> 01:16:27,542
[SPEAKER_33]: And I think it's going to create a pretty noisy environment and I appreciate the discussion about how to manage that and, and students need to answer to their university and so forth but that's kind of complicated maybe not realistic because they're at different universities, what does that mean and what takes priority the city's noise ordinance or the university.

778
01:16:29,197 --> 01:16:37,524
[SPEAKER_33]: And then just the number of people I'd like to hear how many people we're talking about in this building, because you're saying two beds in a bedroom.

779
01:16:37,784 --> 01:16:38,685
[SPEAKER_33]: How many bedrooms?

780
01:16:39,005 --> 01:16:46,912
[SPEAKER_33]: I mean, there's a lot of factors that can go into putting a lot of people in here, especially if the height requirements stay as high as you're talking about.

781
01:16:46,952 --> 01:16:48,833
[SPEAKER_33]: So I, too, am an advocate of that.

782
01:16:49,743 --> 01:16:51,744
[SPEAKER_33]: of bringing the heights down.

783
01:16:52,284 --> 01:16:58,886
[SPEAKER_33]: And just circling back to the fraternity-sorority discussion, I think if we don't want those, they should just come out.

784
01:16:58,946 --> 01:17:09,050
[SPEAKER_33]: Because from what I read, most of the off-campus fraternities and sororities, it's true, they're not owned by the students, because that would be unaffordable.

785
01:17:09,110 --> 01:17:10,730
[SPEAKER_33]: But they're also not owned by the national chapters.

786
01:17:10,750 --> 01:17:17,173
[SPEAKER_33]: They're actually purchased and created by groups of alumni and then rented out to students.

787
01:17:18,393 --> 01:17:20,676
[SPEAKER_33]: alumni actually probably would have some buying power.

788
01:17:20,856 --> 01:17:25,963
[SPEAKER_33]: So if we don't want them, they just should not be in there.

789
01:17:29,135 --> 01:17:30,096
[SPEAKER_33]: Those are my comments.

790
01:17:30,556 --> 01:17:37,702
[SPEAKER_33]: I do feel like, I don't know, I don't know where everyone from Hillside is because everybody I talked to says they don't really want a dorm.

791
01:17:38,042 --> 01:17:48,851
[SPEAKER_33]: And I, and then some are surprised that they're hearing about it for the first time, which surprises me, but because there's been a lot of discussion about it, but I think people don't quite know.

792
01:17:49,051 --> 01:17:53,595
[SPEAKER_33]: So yeah, I think you're, you're going to find you're catching people by surprise.

793
01:17:55,957 --> 01:17:56,217
[SPEAKER_33]: Thank you.

794
01:17:57,919 --> 01:17:58,639
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you Laura.

795
01:17:59,440 --> 01:18:05,043
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll go back to in person name and address for the record and you'll have three minutes.

796
01:18:05,704 --> 01:18:06,304
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much.

797
01:18:06,725 --> 01:18:10,507
[SPEAKER_05]: Pat Gallagher I'm here with Goulston and stores on behalf of Tufts University.

798
01:18:11,087 --> 01:18:17,932
[SPEAKER_05]: Just wanted to quickly weigh in on the student housing proposal that we've heard about tonight.

799
01:18:19,461 --> 01:18:25,065
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think we're still digesting this and understand that a lot of thought has gone into this.

800
01:18:25,585 --> 01:18:28,648
[SPEAKER_05]: We do have some concerns from what we've seen so far.

801
01:18:29,028 --> 01:18:31,030
[SPEAKER_05]: This is not something that Tufts is involved in.

802
01:18:32,531 --> 01:18:46,282
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think, frankly, based on the minimum size that is being discussed, we'd have some concerns on a supply and demand standpoint and whether there's really enough demand to support that size of a development.

803
01:18:47,138 --> 01:18:57,744
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think from a supervision standpoint as well, when Tufts thinks about its dormitories, these are buildings that have Tufts resident assistants.

804
01:18:57,924 --> 01:19:00,185
[SPEAKER_05]: They are part of the university.

805
01:19:01,146 --> 01:19:08,850
[SPEAKER_05]: And so to have a facility that doesn't have that same sort of structure is something that I think, you know, we would need to think about.

806
01:19:08,950 --> 01:19:15,174
[SPEAKER_05]: So, you know, still kind of reviewing the proposal, thinking about it, but wanted to echo that I think

807
01:19:15,633 --> 01:19:17,714
[SPEAKER_05]: Right now, Tufts has some concerns with that as well.

808
01:19:18,074 --> 01:19:18,375
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

809
01:19:32,162 --> 01:19:32,462
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

810
01:19:32,702 --> 01:19:41,327
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm going to go to Jenny Gilbert on Zoom next, and then we'll go back to the podium in person, and then we'll go to David Roach, and then Lori Krieger on Zoom.

811
01:19:41,467 --> 01:19:42,548
[SPEAKER_08]: So, Jenny.

812
01:19:46,325 --> 01:19:51,687
[SPEAKER_03]: Hi, my name is Jenny Gilbert, and I live on North street.

813
01:19:51,767 --> 01:19:56,428
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm actually neighbors with Laura and I agree.

814
01:19:56,608 --> 01:20:04,231
[SPEAKER_03]: I support mixed use housing, but I'm really concerned about the height of the buildings and the.

815
01:20:05,264 --> 01:20:07,946
[SPEAKER_03]: the plan for the dorms especially.

816
01:20:07,966 --> 01:20:11,169
[SPEAKER_03]: I've lived on North Street for about three years.

817
01:20:11,309 --> 01:20:12,510
[SPEAKER_03]: We have a lot of traffic.

818
01:20:12,530 --> 01:20:13,751
[SPEAKER_03]: We have a lot of heavy traffic.

819
01:20:13,811 --> 01:20:16,233
[SPEAKER_03]: We have a lot of trucks going up and down the street.

820
01:20:17,413 --> 01:20:20,896
[SPEAKER_03]: The road is in really bad condition right now.

821
01:20:21,637 --> 01:20:28,982
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think I just feel like without a solid traffic plan, but even with one,

822
01:20:30,101 --> 01:20:35,265
[SPEAKER_03]: putting that many people in the neighborhood will really be a crisis for congestion.

823
01:20:35,285 --> 01:20:46,635
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, this year, when we had the snowstorms and one side of the road was closed, people had to park blocks away from their house who didn't have parking.

824
01:20:46,695 --> 01:20:49,057
[SPEAKER_03]: And not everybody has a driveway on the street.

825
01:20:50,338 --> 01:20:56,262
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, so I just wanted to express my concern about those things.

826
01:20:56,523 --> 01:20:56,843
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

827
01:21:00,982 --> 01:21:01,402
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

828
01:21:01,482 --> 01:21:03,604
[SPEAKER_08]: We're going to go next to the podium.

829
01:21:03,804 --> 01:21:06,325
[SPEAKER_08]: If you give your name and your neighborhood and you'll have three minutes.

830
01:21:06,646 --> 01:21:06,826
[SPEAKER_23]: Okay.

831
01:21:07,286 --> 01:21:07,766
[SPEAKER_23]: Good evening.

832
01:21:07,826 --> 01:21:09,007
[SPEAKER_23]: My name is Lorraine Thornhill.

833
01:21:09,547 --> 01:21:16,592
[SPEAKER_23]: I live on North Street for over 20 something years and I'm concerned about

834
01:21:17,748 --> 01:21:25,211
[SPEAKER_23]: It's great to bring a mixed-use building, but I'm concerned about the height that I'm seeing here, about seven stories.

835
01:21:25,331 --> 01:21:28,492
[SPEAKER_23]: Also, I'm not clear about how many people are going to be in this building.

836
01:21:29,292 --> 01:21:31,953
[SPEAKER_23]: As I just heard Jenny say, I believe we're neighbors.

837
01:21:34,803 --> 01:21:37,565
[SPEAKER_23]: When there was a snow emergency, where is it going to be parking?

838
01:21:37,986 --> 01:21:43,610
[SPEAKER_23]: Boston Ave is a main artery, so there is no parking on Boston Ave when there's during a snow emergency.

839
01:21:44,451 --> 01:21:55,520
[SPEAKER_23]: And on North Street right now, already during this last major, major snow storms that we had, there was not sufficient parking and everybody does not have parking garages.

840
01:21:55,661 --> 01:21:57,822
[SPEAKER_23]: Are we also considering, um,

841
01:21:58,923 --> 01:22:03,765
[SPEAKER_23]: the residences, the residents that live around there, and do they know about this proposal?

842
01:22:04,305 --> 01:22:06,446
[SPEAKER_23]: I happen to hear about it through somebody else.

843
01:22:06,907 --> 01:22:10,288
[SPEAKER_23]: Everybody, as you can see, does not attend these meetings or watch these meetings.

844
01:22:10,888 --> 01:22:15,890
[SPEAKER_23]: Is there going to be signage or are we going to get a reverse call to say what is going on?

845
01:22:15,950 --> 01:22:18,692
[SPEAKER_23]: How can we voice our opinion about this?

846
01:22:18,792 --> 01:22:21,713
[SPEAKER_23]: But I am very concerned about this

847
01:22:23,579 --> 01:22:28,043
[SPEAKER_23]: dormitory or housing that we are proposing to have of seven.

848
01:22:28,183 --> 01:22:29,464
[SPEAKER_23]: What I heard was six stories.

849
01:22:29,945 --> 01:22:31,246
[SPEAKER_23]: I'm not too sure if that is true.

850
01:22:32,067 --> 01:22:33,428
[SPEAKER_23]: So I'm just very concerned.

851
01:22:33,648 --> 01:22:34,009
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you.

852
01:22:35,730 --> 01:22:36,171
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

853
01:22:36,191 --> 01:22:41,596
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm going to go to David on Zoom.

854
01:22:41,656 --> 01:22:47,982
[SPEAKER_08]: David, if you could provide your name and your city or neighborhood for the record and you'll have three minutes.

855
01:22:51,946 --> 01:22:57,231
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you, David Roach, representing the owners of 222 Boston Avenue.

856
01:22:57,251 --> 01:23:01,674
[SPEAKER_19]: I'd just like to clarify one thing out of the gate, talking about the use here.

857
01:23:03,296 --> 01:23:05,718
[SPEAKER_19]: This is just a proposal for an allowed use.

858
01:23:06,258 --> 01:23:12,403
[SPEAKER_19]: Obviously, there's a long way to go between approving zoning and realizing a project.

859
01:23:14,105 --> 01:23:16,367
[SPEAKER_19]: There could be a multifamily mixed use building here.

860
01:23:16,407 --> 01:23:19,249
[SPEAKER_19]: There could be many other uses.

861
01:23:21,381 --> 01:23:27,667
[SPEAKER_19]: But we're just trying to keep the options open here as this zoning moves through.

862
01:23:28,748 --> 01:23:37,315
[SPEAKER_19]: We've had folks expressed interest in this as a potential use, so we thought it would be a good idea to have it be allowed.

863
01:23:39,317 --> 01:23:42,300
[SPEAKER_19]: Obviously, if there is not a demand, it won't get built.

864
01:23:45,277 --> 01:23:50,039
[SPEAKER_19]: But it does represent an opportunity to get students out of the two and three family homes.

865
01:23:50,340 --> 01:23:57,283
[SPEAKER_19]: And I don't know why it would be a bad thing to create that kind of opportunity within the co.

866
01:23:58,484 --> 01:24:13,932
[SPEAKER_19]: As for the use in its definition, the CDB did a great job last night, I believe, of crafting some detailed language to protect the best interests of the city as it relates to this potential use.

867
01:24:15,011 --> 01:24:34,240
[SPEAKER_19]: I was a bit surprised to see it being discussed as a CDB reviewed use because a special permit really exists for uses that are simple and vague to create these guardrails that the CDB was spending last night crafting.

868
01:24:35,981 --> 01:24:43,905
[SPEAKER_19]: There's a significant amount of conditions that were proposed that would typically be the kind of conditions that are crafted in a special permit.

869
01:24:44,426 --> 01:24:49,469
[SPEAKER_19]: And I was expecting that the purpose of that was to create this as a buy right use.

870
01:24:50,390 --> 01:24:52,371
[SPEAKER_19]: So a little surprised by that being discussed.

871
01:24:53,431 --> 01:24:59,315
[SPEAKER_19]: As for the height shown, I have to be honest, I've been in this business for a long time.

872
01:24:59,335 --> 01:25:05,258
[SPEAKER_19]: I think shadow studies are not the best way to represent really anything.

873
01:25:06,399 --> 01:25:09,601
[SPEAKER_19]: Picking the time of day, the time of year, no one really

874
01:25:10,054 --> 01:25:12,054
[SPEAKER_19]: could ever agree on what is a good amount of shadows.

875
01:25:12,074 --> 01:25:16,335
[SPEAKER_19]: To every neighbor, any shadow is too much.

876
01:25:16,856 --> 01:25:24,017
[SPEAKER_19]: The reality is that a large building will cast shadows and it will never make it look in a favorable light.

877
01:25:24,537 --> 01:25:39,401
[SPEAKER_19]: But the proposed heights that were shown within the shadow studies for the BA3 zone were a bit surprising along North Avenue based upon the past discussions initially.

878
01:25:40,219 --> 01:25:45,182
[SPEAKER_19]: and has had proposed in this zone a 98 foot height for North Avenue.

879
01:25:46,623 --> 01:25:53,727
[SPEAKER_19]: And I would remind folks that the current zoning allows for 85 feet, which is the equivalent of seven stories.

880
01:25:53,807 --> 01:26:03,552
[SPEAKER_19]: So to limit that to five stories is surprising and would create building forms that are really not buildable and the incentive zoning would be watered down.

881
01:26:03,632 --> 01:26:05,253
[SPEAKER_19]: So I would just consider that

882
01:26:05,973 --> 01:26:16,561
[SPEAKER_19]: A step back, as shown on Boston Avenue, would still give the protections of not creating a large wall, as I think is the primary fear of most folks when it comes to tall buildings.

883
01:26:16,601 --> 01:26:21,665
[SPEAKER_19]: So a step back is appropriate, but limiting the height overall doesn't make much sense to us.

884
01:26:22,586 --> 01:26:23,327
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you for your time.

885
01:26:25,809 --> 01:26:26,289
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

886
01:26:27,250 --> 01:26:29,371
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll go back to in-person.

887
01:26:29,391 --> 01:26:33,855
[SPEAKER_08]: You can provide your name and your neighborhood for the record, and you'll have three minutes.

888
01:26:35,670 --> 01:26:37,253
[SPEAKER_18]: Mary Anna Ducey to North Street.

889
01:26:38,895 --> 01:26:44,144
[SPEAKER_18]: If I'm correct the Connor I'm concerned with the corner of Boston Avenue North Street.

890
01:26:44,805 --> 01:26:47,749
[SPEAKER_18]: If I'm correct you said that that would be six plus two.

891
01:26:51,796 --> 01:26:57,500
[SPEAKER_15]: And North Street is, well, it depends on which scenario you want to look at.

892
01:26:57,540 --> 01:26:59,561
[SPEAKER_08]: Marianne, if you could just direct your comments here.

893
01:27:01,123 --> 01:27:01,703
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm just correct.

894
01:27:01,723 --> 01:27:02,924
[SPEAKER_08]: Boston and North?

895
01:27:02,964 --> 01:27:03,684
[SPEAKER_08]: Boston and North.

896
01:27:04,445 --> 01:27:06,286
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, there's three proposals.

897
01:27:06,466 --> 01:27:08,187
[SPEAKER_18]: I want the maximum.

898
01:27:08,207 --> 01:27:10,969
[SPEAKER_08]: 5 plus 2, 6 plus 1, or 6 plus 2.

899
01:27:11,009 --> 01:27:12,190
[SPEAKER_08]: So those are the three proposals.

900
01:27:12,210 --> 01:27:13,411
[SPEAKER_08]: 6 plus 2 would be the maximum.

901
01:27:13,851 --> 01:27:14,572
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes, that's the height.

902
01:27:14,592 --> 01:27:17,034
[SPEAKER_18]: Okay, which I would be opposed to that height.

903
01:27:17,915 --> 01:27:38,552
[SPEAKER_18]: At a previous meeting I asked Chair, well I didn't ask Chair Carr, I asked all of you to walk Boston Ave to get a visual of what's there today and try to visualize what you're proposing here and Doug Carr did that and he said at the last meeting, which I think is helpful.

904
01:27:40,814 --> 01:27:56,148
[SPEAKER_18]: The other thing I would like to bring out at the end of the last meeting, President Beers, in a discussion with Danielle from the CD office, you said this, just because we increase zoning doesn't mean they will build.

905
01:27:56,508 --> 01:27:57,729
[SPEAKER_18]: Well, of course they will build.

906
01:27:58,150 --> 01:28:00,112
[SPEAKER_18]: A developer will come and somebody will build.

907
01:28:00,932 --> 01:28:03,174
[SPEAKER_18]: So we should not over

908
01:28:04,425 --> 01:28:13,252
[SPEAKER_18]: zone, not create higher, we should put the ideal, not the maximum, because someone will come along and make the maximum.

909
01:28:14,673 --> 01:28:19,196
[SPEAKER_18]: As far as the North Street corner, the land slopes down.

910
01:28:20,117 --> 01:28:26,461
[SPEAKER_18]: The part closest to the track is lower than the part on Boston Ave, so I don't know how

911
01:28:27,822 --> 01:28:33,845
[SPEAKER_18]: if you do a step building or what you would do there, but an eight-story building there would be a lot.

912
01:28:34,926 --> 01:28:47,653
[SPEAKER_18]: I've asked the mayor's office, and I'll ask all of you, I mentioned it at a previous meeting, to do a traffic study on Boston Ave, because the traffic on Boston Ave today is not good.

913
01:28:49,254 --> 01:28:58,481
[SPEAKER_18]: especially during rush hours, it takes four to five changes of lights to go from Nodd Street through the Winthrop Street traffic light.

914
01:28:59,361 --> 01:29:03,685
[SPEAKER_18]: And people tell me, I don't go out that early in the morning, but they tell me it's the same in the morning.

915
01:29:04,385 --> 01:29:10,089
[SPEAKER_18]: That's today, without the addition of potentially 900 people living there.

916
01:29:10,370 --> 01:29:14,032
[SPEAKER_18]: Because Walkland Court is going to start construction, we got a letter this week,

917
01:29:15,033 --> 01:29:15,833
[SPEAKER_18]: very shortly.

918
01:29:16,534 --> 01:29:20,675
[SPEAKER_18]: So when that's finished, there's going to be 300 to 350 people there.

919
01:29:20,995 --> 01:29:28,378
[SPEAKER_18]: Plus, if you could potentially put 600 people in a dormitory, not all of them will have cars, but many will have cars.

920
01:29:28,458 --> 01:29:30,599
[SPEAKER_18]: You'll have that many more people on Boston Ave.

921
01:29:31,279 --> 01:29:38,902
[SPEAKER_18]: So before you decide anything here, that traffic study has to be done, and it has to wait till September, till the students come back from Tufts.

922
01:29:41,043 --> 01:29:43,024
[SPEAKER_18]: So I haven't heard back from the mayor yet.

923
01:29:44,004 --> 01:29:46,365
[SPEAKER_18]: She's out of town today or yesterday.

924
01:29:48,626 --> 01:29:51,347
[SPEAKER_18]: So basically that's my position.

925
01:29:52,268 --> 01:29:52,608
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

926
01:29:53,488 --> 01:29:53,988
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

927
01:29:54,669 --> 01:29:57,710
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll go to Jonah on Zoom.

928
01:29:58,651 --> 01:30:03,993
[SPEAKER_08]: Jonah if you could provide your name and neighborhood and you'll have three minutes.

929
01:30:06,793 --> 01:30:07,313
[SPEAKER_01]: Hi, thank you.

930
01:30:07,393 --> 01:30:11,195
[SPEAKER_01]: My name is Jonah Dakota and in South Medford.

931
01:30:13,196 --> 01:30:15,297
[SPEAKER_01]: And I have a few questions.

932
01:30:15,917 --> 01:30:19,719
[SPEAKER_01]: Am I allowed to get responses at this point?

933
01:30:20,479 --> 01:30:25,261
[SPEAKER_01]: Or is it just going to be some recorded record of a question?

934
01:30:26,862 --> 01:30:27,802
[SPEAKER_01]: Can you even answer that?

935
01:30:29,323 --> 01:30:34,225
[SPEAKER_08]: If you use your comment period and you ask questions, we'll keep a recorded record of the questions.

936
01:30:34,660 --> 01:31:02,493
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay, so I feel that I'm confused because in the last meeting that I attended via Zoom, in response from the planners to the outrage over the shadowing of the Tufts building and the proposal for shadow lines at a 45 degree angle from the property line,

937
01:31:03,700 --> 01:31:12,165
[SPEAKER_01]: that that's been appearing, at least from the shadow study that we saw this evening, ignored.

938
01:31:13,426 --> 01:31:22,511
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm wondering about, of course, it relates to the height complaints that we've heard before and the shadowing that was demonstrated.

939
01:31:23,932 --> 01:31:31,996
[SPEAKER_01]: And the second piece of my question about shadowing is that the sun in February is 10 degrees

940
01:31:34,292 --> 01:31:36,153
[SPEAKER_01]: higher than it is in December.

941
01:31:36,893 --> 01:31:51,276
[SPEAKER_01]: And I understand that some choice was made to show this in February as the deepest shadow time, rather than the winter solstice in December, where the shadows were most extreme.

942
01:31:52,517 --> 01:31:56,958
[SPEAKER_01]: I was under the impression that shadows were going to be observed

943
01:31:57,926 --> 01:32:00,408
[SPEAKER_01]: when it came to height restrictions.

944
01:32:01,009 --> 01:32:09,716
[SPEAKER_01]: And there was an explanation about larger buildings in Medford Square and using the highway as a buffer for that height.

945
01:32:10,837 --> 01:32:12,038
[SPEAKER_01]: And has that been ignored?

946
01:32:13,399 --> 01:32:20,606
[SPEAKER_01]: Because if it has been, then we need to revisit at least the public comment about shadow lines.

947
01:32:21,186 --> 01:32:25,310
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm of the opinion as to what's already been expressed

948
01:32:26,573 --> 01:32:45,838
[SPEAKER_01]: Through some folks here, I share their opinion that having sunlight in your life, in your day, blocked out by tall buildings, or even short buildings on a tall hill, would be a problem for their neighborhoods, for the people who live there.

949
01:32:46,917 --> 01:33:12,935
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'd like to actually get some response to where the deviation from the clear explanation in the last meeting about being conservative with building heights and their effect on shadowing neighboring properties as a response to the problems that we've already created for those that live near the larger science building in Tufts.

950
01:33:13,116 --> 01:33:13,496
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

951
01:33:15,737 --> 01:33:16,538
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you for your comment.

952
01:33:17,525 --> 01:33:20,026
[SPEAKER_08]: We will go back to the chamber.

953
01:33:20,187 --> 01:33:22,288
[SPEAKER_08]: I think we have someone who'd like to speak in person.

954
01:33:22,308 --> 01:33:25,470
[SPEAKER_08]: If you could provide your name and your neighborhood, and you'll have three minutes.

955
01:33:27,531 --> 01:33:31,813
[SPEAKER_17]: Angela Murphy, 16 Carding Street, and I've been on Carding Street for 70 years.

956
01:33:34,103 --> 01:33:37,686
[SPEAKER_17]: And we moved to Carding Street because it was not a condensed neighborhood.

957
01:33:38,206 --> 01:33:44,951
[SPEAKER_17]: We had a chance to move to Somerville, but we didn't because there was land and green space at the house we purchased.

958
01:33:45,712 --> 01:33:54,379
[SPEAKER_17]: So I want to say right now I am opposed to having four, six, eight, and ten story buildings along the Boston Ave corridor.

959
01:33:55,179 --> 01:33:56,540
[SPEAKER_17]: If you must build,

960
01:33:57,441 --> 01:34:15,643
[SPEAKER_17]: then limit the buildings to four stories with no incentives to go higher because the higher the buildings, the more they will cast a shadow over the surrounding neighborhoods of single family and two and three story buildings down elevation from the hillside.

961
01:34:17,530 --> 01:34:29,553
[SPEAKER_17]: The recommendations for providing green space is not guaranteed, as I understand from being to another meeting, because the green space you provide may not be sustained.

962
01:34:30,153 --> 01:34:41,396
[SPEAKER_17]: And a rooftop garden does not benefit the neighborhood because it's not visible to the neighbors, and it is only usable to the residents in the particular building.

963
01:34:41,956 --> 01:34:45,157
[SPEAKER_17]: So that, to me, is useless green space for the neighborhood.

964
01:34:46,263 --> 01:35:02,158
[SPEAKER_17]: A traffic study needs to be done and adequate parking provided for residents in the buildings so that vehicles do not spill onto the surrounding streets, and fix the roads to accommodate the extra traffic.

965
01:35:03,019 --> 01:35:09,345
[SPEAKER_17]: Right now, Boston Avenue is in such disrepair that you can break an axle if you go in some of the holes.

966
01:35:10,703 --> 01:35:24,091
[SPEAKER_17]: When I asked why you are preparing higher density housing in the Hillside neighborhood and throughout Method, it was said, if I understand correctly, I hear it, that there are people who wish to live this way.

967
01:35:25,132 --> 01:35:30,555
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, since this affects the established surrounding neighborhood, I wish to ask for you

968
01:35:31,576 --> 01:35:40,202
[SPEAKER_17]: to walk the neighborhoods, walk the streets, canvas the people who own the houses there or reside in the houses there.

969
01:35:40,982 --> 01:35:50,448
[SPEAKER_17]: You have meetings, however, communication about where and when these meetings take place has been lacking and insufficient.

970
01:35:50,908 --> 01:35:53,310
[SPEAKER_17]: I only find out at last minute sometimes.

971
01:35:55,305 --> 01:36:23,501
[SPEAKER_17]: If you actually walk the neighborhoods in Boston Ave, you would see it is a vibrant hub of activity for all who reside there in the Hillside neighborhood and hopefully see that what you would propose would have negative effects in many ways to the people who have lived there over the long term or moved there because they moved there to take advantage of what the neighborhood offered.

972
01:36:25,407 --> 01:36:45,755
[SPEAKER_17]: Any business you approve should, I'm sorry, any business you should approve, I'll be a little longer, accommodate all who reside in the Hillside neighborhood and provide services for students, families and seniors alike and be accessible to all and provide parking you would need for those who aren't able to walk.

973
01:36:46,155 --> 01:36:54,799
[SPEAKER_17]: It's nice to say you have walkable neighborhoods, but there's people at a certain age or people, families with children who can't always walk.

974
01:36:56,124 --> 01:36:57,105
[SPEAKER_17]: to these neighborhoods.

975
01:36:59,727 --> 01:37:03,591
[SPEAKER_17]: And the businesses that are there now are established.

976
01:37:04,151 --> 01:37:22,487
[SPEAKER_17]: And it would be a shame to lose any of them, as it was a great loss to lose the Hillside Hardware Store, which was known throughout the state in New Hampshire as the store to go to for paint, and prominently displayed and promoted over TV stations at different times on different programs.

977
01:37:23,667 --> 01:37:28,410
[SPEAKER_17]: These buildings will accommodate many new residents and put a strain on our grid.

978
01:37:29,330 --> 01:37:43,318
[SPEAKER_17]: I was informed that they are having rolling blackouts weekly in random neighborhoods throughout Somerville because it is so densely populated that their grid cannot handle the load.

979
01:37:44,178 --> 01:37:48,861
[SPEAKER_17]: And not just for a few minutes, but for two to three hours at a time.

980
01:37:48,981 --> 01:37:50,542
[SPEAKER_17]: My cousin lives in Somerville.

981
01:37:51,838 --> 01:37:54,262
[SPEAKER_08]: Angela, you're over by about a minute now, so if you could wrap up.

982
01:37:54,342 --> 01:37:55,884
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm sorry, can I just wrap up?

983
01:37:55,944 --> 01:37:56,946
[SPEAKER_17]: I have just a couple more things.

984
01:37:57,006 --> 01:37:57,827
[SPEAKER_08]: In a sentence or two, yeah.

985
01:37:58,488 --> 01:38:08,042
[SPEAKER_17]: Why are we accommodating Tufts in some instances at the expense of the negative effects the proposal will have on the Hillside neighborhood?

986
01:38:10,213 --> 01:38:20,736
[SPEAKER_17]: If they need to enroll students, more students, and they need to have housing for them, why isn't it not possible for them to build up on their already existing campus housing?

987
01:38:21,416 --> 01:38:24,617
[SPEAKER_17]: And yes, this proposal is not done right.

988
01:38:25,117 --> 01:38:36,820
[SPEAKER_17]: If it's not done right, we'll create a transient community and an established neighborhood where neighbors know neighbors and take pride in owning a home in Meffitt, surrounded by green space.

989
01:38:37,400 --> 01:38:38,140
[SPEAKER_08]: Angela, thank you.

990
01:38:39,750 --> 01:38:40,130
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

991
01:38:41,271 --> 01:38:42,952
[SPEAKER_08]: Go to Lori on Zoom.

992
01:38:43,112 --> 01:38:46,974
[SPEAKER_08]: Lori Krieger, if you give your name and your neighborhood and you'll have three minutes.

993
01:38:47,235 --> 01:38:49,996
[SPEAKER_13]: Hey, I'm Lori Krieger at Medford Hillside.

994
01:38:50,156 --> 01:38:51,357
[SPEAKER_13]: Nice to see you all again.

995
01:38:51,377 --> 01:39:02,724
[SPEAKER_13]: I want to thank the CBD and Alicia and all of y'all for the updates that you made from yesterday and looking to close the loopholes so that we can really make sure that housing is for people.

996
01:39:03,345 --> 01:39:07,147
[SPEAKER_13]: I think whatever we can do to ensure that it's really, really super important.

997
01:39:08,595 --> 01:39:24,440
[SPEAKER_13]: I think that from my vantage point, I know like if we can make some of these buildings a little more human scale, and that if we can at all, incentives for affordable and moderate housing to be as high a percentage as we can possibly make it, 20% still feels too small to me.

998
01:39:25,781 --> 01:39:32,863
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm still wondering if a significant amount of storefronts were made on Boston Avenue, how it would impact Medford Square.

999
01:39:33,638 --> 01:39:45,002
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm just I know I'm being a little bit redundant but I just every square has empty storefronts and every main artery has empty storefront so why, how do we make sure that it's used.

1000
01:39:45,222 --> 01:39:46,302
[SPEAKER_13]: That's all I care about.

1001
01:39:46,862 --> 01:39:48,243
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm not all but mostly.

1002
01:39:49,588 --> 01:39:57,593
[SPEAKER_13]: Today, the President of the United States refused to sign the Affordable Housing Bill, which eliminates the ability of venture capitalists to buy up whole neighborhoods.

1003
01:39:58,054 --> 01:40:08,581
[SPEAKER_13]: How can we as a city or at a state level protect our communities for people to live in their homes or to live in their neighborhoods instead of it being just money for money's sake somewhere?

1004
01:40:08,601 --> 01:40:12,764
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm seeing more homes for sale on the hillside than I ever have.

1005
01:40:13,204 --> 01:40:15,345
[SPEAKER_13]: And I'm really curious as to what's prompting this.

1006
01:40:15,926 --> 01:40:17,647
[SPEAKER_13]: Is it that greed quotient?

1007
01:40:19,011 --> 01:40:24,076
[SPEAKER_13]: And basically, I'm looking at more people talking about a concept called ethical capitalism.

1008
01:40:24,777 --> 01:40:30,423
[SPEAKER_13]: And I think that our long term goals, it's essential that we really focus on human environmental centered design.

1009
01:40:31,083 --> 01:40:34,767
[SPEAKER_13]: Whatever we do, it's got to help the living, breathing things on this planet.

1010
01:40:35,488 --> 01:40:39,813
[SPEAKER_13]: And this moment of unregulated capitalism won't last forever.

1011
01:40:40,600 --> 01:40:45,681
[SPEAKER_13]: And in terms of Tufts and the VCs, watch what they do, not what they say.

1012
01:40:46,001 --> 01:40:49,702
[SPEAKER_13]: Let's be super mindful that it was five stories.

1013
01:40:49,762 --> 01:40:51,663
[SPEAKER_13]: Tufts was going to be five-story buildings.

1014
01:40:51,743 --> 01:40:55,424
[SPEAKER_13]: And then it took a minute, but they became 10 stories.

1015
01:40:55,824 --> 01:40:57,524
[SPEAKER_13]: And there was nothing we can do about it.

1016
01:40:58,064 --> 01:41:02,785
[SPEAKER_13]: And I will no longer get to use the sun to melt the ice on my driveway in the winter.

1017
01:41:03,266 --> 01:41:03,846
[SPEAKER_13]: So I know.

1018
01:41:04,606 --> 01:41:05,886
[SPEAKER_13]: Anyway, thank you all so much.

1019
01:41:08,587 --> 01:41:09,167
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Lori.

1020
01:41:10,812 --> 01:41:13,153
[SPEAKER_08]: Is there anyone who hasn't spoken yet in person who'd like to speak?

1021
01:41:13,193 --> 01:41:14,314
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes, come on up.

1022
01:41:19,137 --> 01:41:21,358
[SPEAKER_08]: Give your name and your neighbourhood, and you'll have three minutes.

1023
01:41:21,498 --> 01:41:24,280
[SPEAKER_09]: My name is Rita Donnelly, and I live at 35 Johnwood Road.

1024
01:41:25,000 --> 01:41:27,822
[SPEAKER_09]: And I would just say I know that we need housing.

1025
01:41:28,562 --> 01:41:29,943
[SPEAKER_09]: I've walked my neighbourhood.

1026
01:41:30,844 --> 01:41:37,468
[SPEAKER_09]: Most of the houses on Orchard Street are owned by realty companies that are renting to tough students.

1027
01:41:38,557 --> 01:41:50,276
[SPEAKER_09]: I heard of four, since the last meeting, I've heard of four houses that have been purchased in Medford by out-of-state people who are using the houses as bed and breakfasts.

1028
01:41:51,203 --> 01:41:56,145
[SPEAKER_09]: Now, when I did the senior abatement, there was a big thing about bed and breakfast, that you had to register with the city.

1029
01:41:56,486 --> 01:42:01,868
[SPEAKER_09]: And I'm wondering if all these people are registered as a business in a bed and breakfast, because I don't think they are.

1030
01:42:02,649 --> 01:42:06,010
[SPEAKER_09]: I mean, four houses, two family houses.

1031
01:42:06,811 --> 01:42:12,874
[SPEAKER_09]: They're keeping one apartment for themselves, the out-of-state person, because their kid goes to Tufts or Harvard or MIT.

1032
01:42:14,014 --> 01:42:17,317
[SPEAKER_09]: And then they're renting out bed and breakfast.

1033
01:42:17,557 --> 01:42:20,079
[SPEAKER_09]: So it's turning into a transient neighborhood.

1034
01:42:20,559 --> 01:42:22,021
[SPEAKER_09]: My neighborhood is a nice neighborhood.

1035
01:42:22,101 --> 01:42:24,543
[SPEAKER_09]: I live on a single family street.

1036
01:42:26,003 --> 01:42:27,504
[SPEAKER_09]: The neighbors are changing now.

1037
01:42:27,564 --> 01:42:28,785
[SPEAKER_09]: The young people are moving in.

1038
01:42:28,805 --> 01:42:30,447
[SPEAKER_09]: The older people are moving away.

1039
01:42:30,607 --> 01:42:32,749
[SPEAKER_09]: And it's nice to see the little kids play.

1040
01:42:33,369 --> 01:42:36,992
[SPEAKER_09]: If you bring in hordes of people, that changes the whole neighborhood.

1041
01:42:37,553 --> 01:42:39,494
[SPEAKER_09]: You can't be bringing in hordes of people.

1042
01:42:39,835 --> 01:42:45,359
[SPEAKER_09]: And yes, it would be nice to have a seven-story building for low-income housing.

1043
01:42:45,639 --> 01:42:47,201
[SPEAKER_09]: There's not going to be no income housing.

1044
01:42:47,221 --> 01:42:50,724
[SPEAKER_09]: You're going to get one or two apartments out of that whole building.

1045
01:42:50,784 --> 01:42:54,407
[SPEAKER_09]: You could have 12 apartments in that building.

1046
01:42:55,180 --> 01:42:57,381
[SPEAKER_09]: You're only going to get one or two affordable housing.

1047
01:42:58,161 --> 01:43:00,562
[SPEAKER_09]: I had a lady, can I say where I work?

1048
01:43:02,242 --> 01:43:04,023
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't want to get in trouble, Jim will kill me.

1049
01:43:04,423 --> 01:43:06,223
[SPEAKER_09]: But anyways, I work at City Hall.

1050
01:43:07,744 --> 01:43:10,925
[SPEAKER_09]: And I had a lady crying because she was going to be evicted.

1051
01:43:12,652 --> 01:43:13,773
[SPEAKER_09]: She had no place to go.

1052
01:43:14,174 --> 01:43:19,819
[SPEAKER_09]: I sent her to the mayor's office because I didn't know what to do with her and she was being evicted and she had no place to go.

1053
01:43:20,179 --> 01:43:20,880
[SPEAKER_09]: I understand.

1054
01:43:21,000 --> 01:43:22,141
[SPEAKER_09]: I was a single parent.

1055
01:43:22,802 --> 01:43:23,623
[SPEAKER_09]: I had three children.

1056
01:43:23,863 --> 01:43:28,147
[SPEAKER_09]: I cannot tell you how many people would not rent to me because I had three boys.

1057
01:43:28,647 --> 01:43:30,529
[SPEAKER_09]: If I had girls, maybe they would think about me.

1058
01:43:31,070 --> 01:43:34,073
[SPEAKER_09]: But because I had three boys, they would not rent to me.

1059
01:43:35,288 --> 01:43:36,549
[SPEAKER_09]: And it was very discouraging.

1060
01:43:36,609 --> 01:43:40,310
[SPEAKER_09]: So I am not opposed to affordable housing.

1061
01:43:40,811 --> 01:43:51,536
[SPEAKER_09]: But there has to be a solution that you can get this affordable housing without changing the neighborhood, without turning it into little, you ever see those hotels in Japan where you just buy the bed?

1062
01:43:52,856 --> 01:43:55,798
[SPEAKER_09]: You can't have that and expect to have a neighborhood.

1063
01:43:56,560 --> 01:44:02,003
[SPEAKER_09]: And you cannot have developers buying up all these houses, reconfiguring them.

1064
01:44:02,083 --> 01:44:04,525
[SPEAKER_09]: The one on North Street, it was a single family home.

1065
01:44:04,705 --> 01:44:06,666
[SPEAKER_09]: There's three apartments in that house now.

1066
01:44:07,006 --> 01:44:07,747
[SPEAKER_09]: It was a developer.

1067
01:44:07,767 --> 01:44:11,249
[SPEAKER_09]: Do you think he's selling it to low income people or renting it to low income people?

1068
01:44:11,629 --> 01:44:12,349
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't think so.

1069
01:44:13,770 --> 01:44:16,212
[SPEAKER_09]: It's a disgrace what's happening to this city.

1070
01:44:17,695 --> 01:44:30,979
[SPEAKER_09]: I really want you to pay attention to what you're doing here, because if you just look at it, oh sorry, if you just look at it in a vacuum as the housing, all right, and not take into account, there are gonna be cars.

1071
01:44:31,579 --> 01:44:33,120
[SPEAKER_09]: I love that parking department.

1072
01:44:33,340 --> 01:44:36,881
[SPEAKER_09]: I call them up, because the people from Tufts are parking on my street.

1073
01:44:37,121 --> 01:44:39,502
[SPEAKER_09]: They don't wanna pay the fees for the garage at Tufts.

1074
01:44:39,962 --> 01:44:44,283
[SPEAKER_09]: So to be having buildings without parking is ridiculous in that neighborhood.

1075
01:44:44,803 --> 01:44:50,425
[SPEAKER_09]: I called the police on one Saturday because I was trying to go up Winter Street to take a right on Boston Ave towards North Street.

1076
01:44:50,905 --> 01:44:52,386
[SPEAKER_09]: And I sat through four sets of lights.

1077
01:44:52,606 --> 01:44:58,848
[SPEAKER_09]: And then when I turned, I couldn't go anywhere because the food people were parking on one side.

1078
01:44:59,149 --> 01:45:02,010
[SPEAKER_09]: They blocked off some of the parking spots or dining.

1079
01:45:02,510 --> 01:45:04,451
[SPEAKER_09]: And the bus couldn't get down the street.

1080
01:45:04,671 --> 01:45:05,331
[SPEAKER_09]: So I called the police.

1081
01:45:05,351 --> 01:45:05,991
[SPEAKER_09]: I said, I'm sitting here.

1082
01:45:06,031 --> 01:45:06,631
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't know what to do.

1083
01:45:06,671 --> 01:45:07,332
[SPEAKER_09]: I can't back up.

1084
01:45:07,352 --> 01:45:08,052
[SPEAKER_09]: People are behind me.

1085
01:45:08,312 --> 01:45:08,952
[SPEAKER_09]: People are in front of me.

1086
01:45:08,972 --> 01:45:09,993
[SPEAKER_09]: And the bus is coming at me.

1087
01:45:10,413 --> 01:45:11,073
[SPEAKER_09]: What do I do?

1088
01:45:11,553 --> 01:45:13,254
[SPEAKER_09]: You have to look at the neighborhood.

1089
01:45:13,834 --> 01:45:15,935
[SPEAKER_09]: and decide how you can meet your goals.

1090
01:45:16,496 --> 01:45:19,498
[SPEAKER_09]: It's not, Salem Street is not like Hillside.

1091
01:45:21,259 --> 01:45:23,140
[SPEAKER_09]: The Square is not like the Hillside.

1092
01:45:24,681 --> 01:45:26,542
[SPEAKER_09]: So just be very mindful.

1093
01:45:26,842 --> 01:45:30,605
[SPEAKER_09]: And when they were doing the Green Line, they were saying, oh, all these people are gonna come.

1094
01:45:31,125 --> 01:45:33,106
[SPEAKER_09]: Now, and this is my last thing.

1095
01:45:34,507 --> 01:45:36,988
[SPEAKER_09]: For Arlington, they're gonna come and take the Green Line.

1096
01:45:37,008 --> 01:45:40,050
[SPEAKER_09]: We have the buses that go to Lechmere, they can take the Green Line.

1097
01:45:40,371 --> 01:45:42,312
[SPEAKER_09]: Now they're gonna eliminate those bus routes.

1098
01:45:43,390 --> 01:45:45,197
[SPEAKER_09]: So what is going to happen to those people?

1099
01:45:45,277 --> 01:45:49,230
[SPEAKER_09]: They're going to be driving to the green line to get to their jobs.

1100
01:45:50,201 --> 01:45:56,145
[SPEAKER_09]: Because people are making decisions just on what they're focusing on and not looking at the bigger picture.

1101
01:45:56,565 --> 01:45:59,747
[SPEAKER_09]: So I'm sorry if I'm crazy, but I really feel passionate about it.

1102
01:45:59,767 --> 01:46:00,927
[SPEAKER_09]: And I love my neighborhood.

1103
01:46:01,568 --> 01:46:03,329
[SPEAKER_09]: And I hope that it doesn't change too much.

1104
01:46:03,409 --> 01:46:12,094
[SPEAKER_09]: But I do understand the plight of people, because I lived it, not being able to rent an apartment, not knowing where I was going to go to get my kids' stuff.

1105
01:46:12,334 --> 01:46:15,716
[SPEAKER_09]: And I did have wonderful people helping me along the way.

1106
01:46:16,637 --> 01:46:17,738
[SPEAKER_09]: So thank you for your time.

1107
01:46:17,918 --> 01:46:18,338
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1108
01:46:23,316 --> 01:46:29,303
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll go to Judy Weinstock on Zoom, name and neighborhood for the record, and you'll have three minutes.

1109
01:46:30,103 --> 01:46:30,864
[SPEAKER_02]: Hi, everybody.

1110
01:46:30,944 --> 01:46:33,607
[SPEAKER_02]: Thanks again for holding the joint meeting.

1111
01:46:33,907 --> 01:46:36,030
[SPEAKER_02]: I think that they're really, really very important.

1112
01:46:36,933 --> 01:46:40,577
[SPEAKER_02]: And as you know, I'm usually here, and here I am again.

1113
01:46:40,597 --> 01:46:44,461
[SPEAKER_02]: A couple of just quick things, and I do want to be pretty brief.

1114
01:46:45,062 --> 01:46:54,752
[SPEAKER_02]: In terms of the potential for non-university student housing on North Street and Boston Avenue, or frankly, anywhere within the one mile of Tufts,

1115
01:46:56,174 --> 01:47:05,368
[SPEAKER_02]: I know it's not the job of the city council or the community development board to worry about things like supply and demand that the marketplace in theory will take care of those things.

1116
01:47:05,969 --> 01:47:10,697
[SPEAKER_02]: But I do know and I feel like you've heard a lot, a lot of pushback.

1117
01:47:10,977 --> 01:47:22,587
[SPEAKER_02]: from the neighborhood around the scope and size and numbers of students that would need to be there to make it a financially feasible project for the developer and the property owner.

1118
01:47:22,607 --> 01:47:30,754
[SPEAKER_02]: I actually have no doubt, and I wrote a letter to this effect, that the property owner will find another very profitable way to use that land.

1119
01:47:31,228 --> 01:47:43,416
[SPEAKER_02]: if in fact this land use is either delayed, as I think it should be, and it'll probably end up being something that's better, actually, for the community.

1120
01:47:44,417 --> 01:47:48,539
[SPEAKER_02]: To someone else's point, who said a lot of people in that neighborhood, it's not my neighborhood.

1121
01:47:48,579 --> 01:47:50,761
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm in the hillside, but I'm not that far down.

1122
01:47:52,927 --> 01:48:12,159
[SPEAKER_02]: It actually has appeared from the public side to be an incredibly speedy process to bring up online a brand new land use, particularly of this type, given the sensitivities of particularly the Hillside neighborhood with regard to all that happened over the last year with Tufts.

1123
01:48:12,960 --> 01:48:20,525
[SPEAKER_02]: I do think that it will be very difficult, even with the regulations that the board has crafted,

1124
01:48:21,646 --> 01:48:27,272
[SPEAKER_02]: to really make it a viable option for the residents who live in that area.

1125
01:48:27,932 --> 01:48:30,375
[SPEAKER_02]: I would like to see a pause placed on it.

1126
01:48:30,435 --> 01:48:34,519
[SPEAKER_02]: I think that it's really only been publicly discussed, I think, for about eight weeks.

1127
01:48:35,260 --> 01:48:39,465
[SPEAKER_02]: I think that's a really, really short period of time to try to craft a brand new land use.

1128
01:48:39,885 --> 01:48:46,288
[SPEAKER_02]: It has this much opposition and needs so much planning in order to move it forward.

1129
01:48:46,829 --> 01:48:49,330
[SPEAKER_02]: And I do think supply and demand is an issue.

1130
01:48:49,470 --> 01:48:58,095
[SPEAKER_02]: And I'm not convinced that it will be a viable option for the developer once Tufts brings up that 10-story dormitory building.

1131
01:48:59,444 --> 01:49:03,606
[SPEAKER_02]: Moving on to the heights issue, I actually think I find it really complicated.

1132
01:49:03,686 --> 01:49:07,408
[SPEAKER_02]: I think that the multiple proposals are really tough to follow.

1133
01:49:09,129 --> 01:49:13,492
[SPEAKER_02]: And I would caution and I think some members of the CD board feel similarly.

1134
01:49:14,452 --> 01:49:19,635
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, you'll have an opportunity to modify zoning in the future.

1135
01:49:19,675 --> 01:49:23,197
[SPEAKER_02]: There shouldn't be a 25 or 30-year break in between reviewing it.

1136
01:49:23,217 --> 01:49:29,901
[SPEAKER_02]: And I would go for more moderation on building heights, and particularly on the corner of Winthrop and Boston Ave.

1137
01:49:29,921 --> 01:49:36,645
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm not sure where the five-story potential on corners has come up or why it's coming up.

1138
01:49:37,365 --> 01:49:43,927
[SPEAKER_02]: But that just seems like sort of overreach on those corners at Boston Avenue and Winthrop.

1139
01:49:44,487 --> 01:49:54,230
[SPEAKER_02]: And with that, I know there's a lot of tensions between the city needing additional revenue and residents needing a break on property taxes and all of that can only come through growth.

1140
01:49:54,790 --> 01:50:07,755
[SPEAKER_02]: So I'm all in favor of growth, but I think that the community development board and the city council need to be a little bit more reserved in allowing really tall buildings to emerge out of this new zoning.

1141
01:50:08,116 --> 01:50:09,516
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much for your time.

1142
01:50:09,556 --> 01:50:10,276
[SPEAKER_02]: I appreciate it.

1143
01:50:11,457 --> 01:50:12,097
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Judy.

1144
01:50:13,878 --> 01:50:17,059
[SPEAKER_08]: Is there anyone in the chambers who hasn't spoken who'd like to speak?

1145
01:50:19,480 --> 01:50:19,760
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

1146
01:50:20,101 --> 01:50:23,142
[SPEAKER_08]: We're going to go to Jeremy Martin on Zoom.

1147
01:50:24,307 --> 01:50:27,413
[SPEAKER_08]: And I think that's our last comment for the hearing tonight.

1148
01:50:27,613 --> 01:50:31,520
[SPEAKER_08]: Jeremy, name and address, name and neighborhood for the record and you'll have three minutes.

1149
01:50:32,403 --> 01:50:35,787
[SPEAKER_21]: Jeremy Martin, I also live in the hillside over on Burgadave.

1150
01:50:37,008 --> 01:50:43,413
[SPEAKER_21]: Thanks for the opportunity to speak again tonight and to be able to see some of the presentation before commenting.

1151
01:50:43,473 --> 01:50:47,637
[SPEAKER_21]: I appreciate the adjustment in the format on that.

1152
01:50:47,657 --> 01:50:53,643
[SPEAKER_21]: I first want to speak up as someone who is very much in favor of added density in our community.

1153
01:50:53,663 --> 01:50:56,846
[SPEAKER_21]: I disagree with the notion that more people

1154
01:50:57,506 --> 01:50:58,767
[SPEAKER_21]: can destroy a neighborhood.

1155
01:50:58,807 --> 01:51:04,511
[SPEAKER_21]: If anything, I think more people makes a neighborhood more vibrant, more lively, more diverse.

1156
01:51:05,511 --> 01:51:07,192
[SPEAKER_21]: And I would like to see that in my community.

1157
01:51:07,232 --> 01:51:12,516
[SPEAKER_21]: And I say that as someone who drives, who bikes, who walks, who has a young child.

1158
01:51:13,036 --> 01:51:16,118
[SPEAKER_21]: Many of the things that people say they had as a value in this

1159
01:51:16,358 --> 01:51:19,380
[SPEAKER_21]: community and why they lived here are the reasons I live here.

1160
01:51:19,441 --> 01:51:22,403
[SPEAKER_21]: And I think it can be a better place even beyond what we know now.

1161
01:51:23,043 --> 01:51:28,548
[SPEAKER_21]: So I very much support the premise of this proposal and what's being considered.

1162
01:51:29,929 --> 01:51:44,141
[SPEAKER_21]: On the student purpose-built housing, I just want to say, I do think that... Jeremy, it looks like you got muted.

1163
01:51:45,710 --> 01:51:47,851
[SPEAKER_08]: or muted yourself, I'm requesting unmute.

1164
01:51:48,211 --> 01:51:48,992
[SPEAKER_21]: Yeah, sorry about that.

1165
01:51:49,152 --> 01:51:49,912
[SPEAKER_21]: Can you hear me now?

1166
01:51:50,693 --> 01:51:50,833
[SPEAKER_08]: Yep.

1167
01:51:51,473 --> 01:51:52,374
[SPEAKER_21]: Yeah, sorry.

1168
01:51:53,314 --> 01:52:05,801
[SPEAKER_21]: I just want to say on that that I want us to consider whether we're working against ourselves if one of the goals of this zoning is to create more housing for the community at large at Medford, and instead replacing

1169
01:52:06,982 --> 01:52:09,564
[SPEAKER_21]: that housing with something that's exclusive for students.

1170
01:52:09,784 --> 01:52:19,951
[SPEAKER_21]: Corners like the one at North Street and any of the other areas of this proposed rezoning are the very places we should be putting buildings for the Medford community, not for students.

1171
01:52:20,071 --> 01:52:21,352
[SPEAKER_21]: Students should be on campus.

1172
01:52:22,032 --> 01:52:26,975
[SPEAKER_21]: And so please consider that we're actually undermining the bigger goal of this entire thing.

1173
01:52:27,676 --> 01:52:30,658
[SPEAKER_21]: And then the last thing I want to focus on is that corner of Winthrop

1174
01:52:31,518 --> 01:52:32,479
[SPEAKER_21]: in Boston Avenue.

1175
01:52:32,499 --> 01:52:40,525
[SPEAKER_21]: I know that Tufts has suggested that four stories is not financially feasible for redevelopment.

1176
01:52:40,545 --> 01:52:48,811
[SPEAKER_21]: I haven't been able to see the details of what the statement is there, but please consider that Tufts is likely not to develop this on their own.

1177
01:52:48,851 --> 01:52:50,472
[SPEAKER_21]: They'll partner with a private developer.

1178
01:52:50,992 --> 01:52:55,416
[SPEAKER_21]: And so you should ask if the interests that are being conveyed are the interests of the university,

1179
01:52:56,056 --> 01:52:58,839
[SPEAKER_21]: Or are they the interests of their for-profit development partner?

1180
01:52:58,859 --> 01:53:05,025
[SPEAKER_21]: This is the same situation that led to a 10-story building, and you've heard many times how that has worked out.

1181
01:53:06,226 --> 01:53:12,312
[SPEAKER_21]: Also remember that it's likely to be a proposal that will be submitted as a Dover project, which will also severely limit

1182
01:53:13,714 --> 01:53:18,641
[SPEAKER_21]: The community development board and any other city boards oversight of the project.

1183
01:53:19,422 --> 01:53:23,828
[SPEAKER_21]: But setting all of that aside, please also take into account the real conditions on this corner.

1184
01:53:23,868 --> 01:53:25,090
[SPEAKER_21]: It's got narrow sidewalks.

1185
01:53:25,170 --> 01:53:26,572
[SPEAKER_21]: It's got fast moving traffic.

1186
01:53:28,554 --> 01:53:37,218
[SPEAKER_21]: And we need to determine if it has the capacity to meet the size of building that's being considered.

1187
01:53:37,839 --> 01:53:45,703
[SPEAKER_21]: I would encourage you to go visit Boston Avenue now and understand the relationship between a relatively narrow sidewalk and a 10-story building.

1188
01:53:46,640 --> 01:53:49,181
[SPEAKER_21]: That's exacerbated even more on this corner.

1189
01:53:49,821 --> 01:53:54,843
[SPEAKER_21]: If this building were to be any more than four or five floors, likely more than four.

1190
01:53:54,903 --> 01:53:56,063
[SPEAKER_21]: What's there now is only two.

1191
01:53:56,203 --> 01:54:05,686
[SPEAKER_21]: So with all of that said, really appreciate the work that everyone has been doing on this and look forward to continuing to review progress.

1192
01:54:05,786 --> 01:54:06,106
[SPEAKER_21]: Thanks.

1193
01:54:09,307 --> 01:54:10,327
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Jeremy.

1194
01:54:11,208 --> 01:54:12,508
[SPEAKER_08]: And thank you to everybody who spoke.

1195
01:54:13,849 --> 01:54:16,272
[SPEAKER_08]: Really, you know, have appreciated the public engagement.

1196
01:54:16,892 --> 01:54:18,614
[SPEAKER_08]: You guys already both spoke.

1197
01:54:23,798 --> 01:54:25,019
[SPEAKER_08]: We already spoke tonight, so.

1198
01:54:25,260 --> 01:54:34,728
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm just, we're going to keep it to what it was, but, you know, everybody had a chance to speak.

1199
01:54:49,962 --> 01:54:50,142
Right.

1200
01:54:54,465 --> 01:54:55,326
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Angela.

1201
01:54:59,810 --> 01:55:04,173
[SPEAKER_08]: We already went through the speaking, so I'm sorry, but we've closed the public hearing for the evening.

1202
01:55:06,255 --> 01:55:08,877
[SPEAKER_08]: We've closed the public hearing, and I gotta follow the rules.

1203
01:55:09,037 --> 01:55:09,698
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm sorry.

1204
01:55:10,158 --> 01:55:10,618
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

1205
01:55:12,740 --> 01:55:14,922
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, I would really prefer that you didn't do that.

1206
01:55:17,962 --> 01:55:21,904
[SPEAKER_18]: Mary Ann, thank you.

1207
01:55:22,145 --> 01:55:23,105
[SPEAKER_18]: All right.

1208
01:55:23,805 --> 01:55:24,186
[SPEAKER_18]: Sure.

1209
01:55:38,961 --> 01:55:53,192
[SPEAKER_22]: A couple people mentioned, just I want to, I don't want to respond, we can't respond to everyone who made comments, but any use that happens, as Emily mentioned in her presentation, there are parking requirements for every use, I believe.

1210
01:55:53,877 --> 01:56:05,845
[SPEAKER_22]: And certainly the North Street, Boston Ave site, the BA3 sites, they're going to have substantial parking, whether it's a multifamily or purpose-built student housing.

1211
01:56:05,885 --> 01:56:06,586
[SPEAKER_22]: It could be a lab.

1212
01:56:06,626 --> 01:56:07,346
[SPEAKER_22]: It could be anything.

1213
01:56:07,967 --> 01:56:09,308
[SPEAKER_22]: But there are parking.

1214
01:56:09,408 --> 01:56:13,250
[SPEAKER_22]: We try to be realistic and recognize that cars exist.

1215
01:56:13,571 --> 01:56:19,195
[SPEAKER_22]: And even though that street is very well served by transit, I do agree with the comments about the buses.

1216
01:56:19,935 --> 01:56:20,715
[SPEAKER_22]: need to be preserved.

1217
01:56:21,236 --> 01:56:28,420
[SPEAKER_22]: We want to get people to that green line that we spent 15 years getting to Medford so that we can take people out of cars where possible.

1218
01:56:28,560 --> 01:56:29,881
[SPEAKER_22]: I know that's not possible for everyone.

1219
01:56:30,661 --> 01:56:32,642
[SPEAKER_22]: I just think that's worth reiterating.

1220
01:56:33,383 --> 01:56:34,143
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, yeah.

1221
01:56:34,203 --> 01:56:36,184
[SPEAKER_08]: And it also came up, you know, a couple of times.

1222
01:56:37,425 --> 01:56:38,746
[SPEAKER_08]: We saw some visuals tonight.

1223
01:56:38,786 --> 01:56:47,811
[SPEAKER_08]: Those visuals do not represent projects that have been proposed or attempts to create, you know, pull permits or even designs that have even been

1224
01:56:49,199 --> 01:56:50,302
[SPEAKER_08]: imagined.

1225
01:56:50,342 --> 01:56:59,601
[SPEAKER_08]: Those are really just kind of attempts to visualize a potential building based on the zoning.

1226
01:57:00,205 --> 01:57:10,972
[SPEAKER_08]: As Emily and Paula noted, most of even the attempted visualizations likely wouldn't be feasible given the dimensional requirements, the parking requirements of the zoning that's proposed.

1227
01:57:11,112 --> 01:57:20,118
[SPEAKER_08]: So even what was shown for the shadow studies, it's unlikely that buildings of that size and mass could be built with the zoning that has been proposed.

1228
01:57:20,878 --> 01:57:25,621
[SPEAKER_08]: So when I say, you know, that the zoning doesn't mean that someone's going to build something, that's what I mean.

1229
01:57:26,862 --> 01:57:28,683
[SPEAKER_08]: There's a lot of things that go into zoning.

1230
01:57:29,211 --> 01:57:45,208
[SPEAKER_08]: I think we took a very, in my view, conservative approach to say, let's make these possible buildings look really big and see what the shadows look like, but with the understanding and the assumptions that Emily and Paola laid out, which is actually even those buildings that were proposed there probably couldn't be built.

1231
01:57:46,109 --> 01:57:48,372
[SPEAKER_08]: And I do think another thing to talk about here, right?

1232
01:57:49,757 --> 01:57:53,539
[SPEAKER_08]: the land values and the building values in the neighborhood are really high.

1233
01:57:54,159 --> 01:57:57,060
[SPEAKER_08]: And that means that building new things is expensive.

1234
01:57:58,421 --> 01:58:11,287
[SPEAKER_08]: And this is one of the things when we talk about environmental benefit or new housing units, there's a reason that projects become more possible when the height limit is higher.

1235
01:58:11,527 --> 01:58:14,128
[SPEAKER_08]: And it's because it's more

1236
01:58:15,492 --> 01:58:18,554
[SPEAKER_08]: environmentally friendly to build a single building.

1237
01:58:19,335 --> 01:58:24,638
[SPEAKER_08]: It's more efficient to build a few more units on a single building than separate those into multiple buildings.

1238
01:58:26,179 --> 01:58:33,344
[SPEAKER_08]: And given the kind of economic environment that we're in right now, that's one of the reasons that some density is really important.

1239
01:58:34,425 --> 01:58:40,649
[SPEAKER_08]: Because if we say no, if we say it's three stories and six units, like, things just don't get built.

1240
01:58:41,970 --> 01:58:51,142
[SPEAKER_08]: So I think when we're talking about finding that middle ground about what change looks like, you know, we could, and I'm not saying anyone's proposing this, right?

1241
01:58:51,582 --> 01:58:55,467
[SPEAKER_08]: No one has said let's put 25 story buildings on Boston Ave, right?

1242
01:58:55,487 --> 01:58:57,890
[SPEAKER_08]: No one from the community development board, no one from the city council.

1243
01:59:00,150 --> 01:59:03,051
[SPEAKER_08]: But you're seeing in Davis Square, and it's different, right?

1244
01:59:03,071 --> 01:59:10,274
[SPEAKER_08]: There is the red line right there, that that is something that someone is coming in and proposing in a relatively nearby neighborhood.

1245
01:59:10,874 --> 01:59:26,580
[SPEAKER_08]: I think that when we talk about three-, four-, five-story buildings and in a very specific area of this zone, in areas that already have some tall warehouse buildings that have been part of our city's history for 100 years, over on Boston and North Street,

1246
01:59:28,436 --> 01:59:30,497
[SPEAKER_08]: This is a scale that is reasonable.

1247
01:59:30,937 --> 01:59:32,238
[SPEAKER_08]: That's my personal opinion.

1248
01:59:34,219 --> 01:59:40,762
[SPEAKER_08]: It's not saying let's just get rid of zoning and let people plop 25-story buildings wherever they want.

1249
01:59:40,862 --> 01:59:43,283
[SPEAKER_08]: Like, I don't think that's an approach that any of us want to take.

1250
01:59:43,723 --> 01:59:45,404
[SPEAKER_08]: But change is difficult.

1251
01:59:46,204 --> 01:59:54,988
[SPEAKER_08]: And adding three to five-story buildings in parts of this corridor and a couple of places where a six or seven-story building would be possible,

1252
01:59:57,622 --> 02:00:07,685
[SPEAKER_08]: is something that is reflective of what it costs to build new buildings and what is feasible change.

1253
02:00:08,745 --> 02:00:11,166
[SPEAKER_08]: So that's my personal perspective.

1254
02:00:11,326 --> 02:00:17,327
[SPEAKER_08]: I think we've spent, you know, three months just talking about this proposed zoning.

1255
02:00:18,168 --> 02:00:26,810
[SPEAKER_08]: Certainly the city council has spent the last two and a half to three years talking about our city's comprehensive plan and housing production plan, our climate plan,

1256
02:00:27,510 --> 02:00:45,470
[SPEAKER_08]: and worked with the Innist Land Strategies Group and the Planning Development Sustainability Office to craft a framework to find reasonable but significant change that makes our neighborhoods more vibrant, that invites mixed uses, that brings in the growth and revenue that folks were talking about.

1257
02:00:45,950 --> 02:00:49,094
[SPEAKER_08]: Because one of the things we don't talk about a lot on these projects is

1258
02:00:49,834 --> 02:00:56,623
[SPEAKER_08]: They will make improvements in the neighborhood, like you will see roads repaired, you will see better sidewalks, you will see new trees.

1259
02:00:57,605 --> 02:01:00,869
[SPEAKER_08]: Those are things that happen when construction is done as well.

1260
02:01:01,330 --> 02:01:02,912
[SPEAKER_08]: It's not going to happen everywhere.

1261
02:01:02,952 --> 02:01:05,074
[SPEAKER_08]: We're not going to have unlimited and infinite money.

1262
02:01:08,367 --> 02:01:25,987
[SPEAKER_08]: The revenue, the way that taxes work, right, in cities and towns, the way that Massachusetts law work is you can either ask the people who live here now to pay more, that's called an override, or you can bring in what's called new growth, and that means allowing construction and new buildings in parts of your city.

1263
02:01:27,709 --> 02:01:28,989
[SPEAKER_08]: and the revenue that comes with that.

1264
02:01:29,630 --> 02:01:46,654
[SPEAKER_08]: And when we're in an environment where the cost of running a city, the cost of fixing streets, the cost of running schools, the cost of paying policemen and firefighters is going up faster than 2.5% per year, that's why we see a lot of the issues that we see as a city.

1265
02:01:46,814 --> 02:01:52,275
[SPEAKER_08]: We don't have enough revenue to pay for even maintaining the services the city provides now.

1266
02:01:53,575 --> 02:01:55,876
[SPEAKER_08]: Growth is essentially other than

1267
02:01:57,522 --> 02:02:01,545
[SPEAKER_08]: asking the people who are here to pay more than 2.5% per year, which is not something that we want to do.

1268
02:02:02,005 --> 02:02:05,107
[SPEAKER_08]: Growth is the only other way to raise revenue to fund city services.

1269
02:02:05,648 --> 02:02:11,312
[SPEAKER_08]: And I think that something that we've talked about for the last three years is how do we have smart, reasonable,

1270
02:02:12,154 --> 02:02:17,058
[SPEAKER_08]: growth that does help raise revenue and improves our neighborhoods.

1271
02:02:17,278 --> 02:02:26,465
[SPEAKER_08]: And I think that this zoning proposal by and large reflects that consensus and the work of planners and a lot of community input over the last six years.

1272
02:02:27,386 --> 02:02:29,207
[SPEAKER_08]: So that's just my two cents on all of that.

1273
02:02:31,309 --> 02:02:36,793
[SPEAKER_08]: With that, do we wanna talk about how we want to deliberate about the, do we wanna start with the heights and the boundaries?

1274
02:02:40,115 --> 02:02:42,441
[SPEAKER_22]: Yes, I just want to make a couple of quick comments.

1275
02:02:44,408 --> 02:03:08,289
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't think there's anybody on either one of these two bodies who's not in favor of a lot of development because the options that we're talking about, even the smallest one of the three, basically the three different tiers of possibilities for BA1, BA2, BA3, I don't even think the small ones are small in my opinion.

1276
02:03:08,469 --> 02:03:12,052
[SPEAKER_22]: And if there's one theme I'm hearing here tonight, it's that

1277
02:03:14,265 --> 02:03:23,109
[SPEAKER_22]: There's a lot of people who are not thrilled with what they think is excessive height on some of the proposals.

1278
02:03:23,809 --> 02:03:30,191
[SPEAKER_22]: And that's the challenges that we, when we talk about, I'm not sure we're talking about the same proposal right now.

1279
02:03:30,271 --> 02:03:33,773
[SPEAKER_22]: Right now we have a menu of three options for three different zones.

1280
02:03:33,813 --> 02:03:39,215
[SPEAKER_22]: So there's potentially nine different zoning tracks we could be going down tonight.

1281
02:03:40,725 --> 02:03:44,287
[SPEAKER_22]: And just one other comment about time.

1282
02:03:45,288 --> 02:03:53,213
[SPEAKER_22]: We spent four months working collectively together on the Medford Square, and we got it right, in my opinion, not perfect, but very good.

1283
02:03:54,794 --> 02:04:01,758
[SPEAKER_22]: As far as I can tell, we've been working, the CD board itself has been working on this for less than six weeks, and I think closer to five.

1284
02:04:03,019 --> 02:04:06,801
[SPEAKER_22]: And so that's 25% of the time for something that is critical.

1285
02:04:06,861 --> 02:04:08,402
[SPEAKER_22]: It's like, I just think,

1286
02:04:09,692 --> 02:04:14,577
[SPEAKER_22]: we need to be a little bit more thoughtful and pace ourselves.

1287
02:04:14,778 --> 02:04:18,061
[SPEAKER_22]: You know, I want to get this done, but I want to get it done right.

1288
02:04:18,101 --> 02:04:21,745
[SPEAKER_22]: And I know that most of the people on the city board share that.

1289
02:04:21,805 --> 02:04:27,392
[SPEAKER_22]: We've said that repeatedly in Meffitt Square, and we're going to continue to say that.

1290
02:04:27,452 --> 02:04:31,096
[SPEAKER_22]: I'm hoping we get consensus, but the next hour or two talking about

1291
02:04:32,459 --> 02:04:39,565
[SPEAKER_22]: about height and massing and options will determine if we're talking about a consensus plan or not.

1292
02:04:40,526 --> 02:04:42,047
[SPEAKER_22]: And that's where I think we stand right now.

1293
02:04:42,127 --> 02:04:44,169
[SPEAKER_22]: So let's talk about the next steps.

1294
02:04:46,230 --> 02:04:46,470
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

1295
02:04:46,490 --> 02:04:51,735
[SPEAKER_08]: I think it would be useful for us to go back through the height and boundary options, like zone by zone.

1296
02:04:53,376 --> 02:04:56,058
[SPEAKER_08]: And I do want to recognize Councilor Scarpelli first.

1297
02:04:57,900 --> 02:04:58,901
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you, Councilor Villescaz.

1298
02:05:00,921 --> 02:05:08,106
[SPEAKER_27]: Before we move forward, I think that understanding the messaging that we're hearing is vital.

1299
02:05:08,146 --> 02:05:26,440
[SPEAKER_27]: I think that going through the process the way we went through the process together with Medford Square, I truly hear and feel that even if people weren't happy with what was finale, they were still content with the process.

1300
02:05:27,121 --> 02:05:29,603
[SPEAKER_27]: And that to me is a victory.

1301
02:05:31,676 --> 02:05:41,245
[SPEAKER_27]: Just to share, I know that I was the one on the mountaintop screaming about community involvement with Salem Street and the concerns we've had.

1302
02:05:41,645 --> 02:05:50,454
[SPEAKER_27]: And I think, to your credit, Mr. President, we took a responsible approach to making sure that we are now listening to our residents.

1303
02:05:55,409 --> 02:06:14,811
[SPEAKER_27]: look at the timeline and I also understand that we do have a tight timeline but at the same time I would concur with Chair Carr in the fact that the process with the height requirements are something we can work through tonight but I've also heard from a lot of people even tonight as I'm sitting here

1304
