[SPEAKER_08]: We excluded Walking Court.

2376
03:25:34,477 --> 03:25:35,058
[SPEAKER_08]: It's BA1.

2377
03:25:35,238 --> 03:25:35,398
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

2378
03:25:38,272 --> 03:25:40,473
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, we didn't necessarily decide.

2379
03:25:40,553 --> 03:25:47,876
[SPEAKER_08]: My personal feeling on it, and I can go to councilors, and I can go to you guys, is if we're keeping the lower heights, let's keep the boundaries as they were proposed.

2380
03:25:48,137 --> 03:25:49,817
[SPEAKER_08]: That's my personal opinion.

2381
03:25:50,077 --> 03:25:51,738
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know if, yeah.

2382
03:25:52,539 --> 03:25:53,579
[SPEAKER_08]: This is for BA1.

2383
03:25:53,599 --> 03:25:57,081
[SPEAKER_08]: There was a proposed, like, boundaries reduction that had been tossed around.

2384
03:25:59,382 --> 03:26:01,843
[SPEAKER_08]: I think we should keep the, leave it as is.

2385
03:26:01,943 --> 03:26:02,183
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

2386
03:26:03,063 --> 03:26:05,044
[SPEAKER_08]: Seems general consensus on the council, leave it as is.

2387
03:26:05,064 --> 03:26:05,585
[SPEAKER_08]: Sure.

2388
03:26:05,605 --> 03:26:06,125
[SPEAKER_08]: CD board.

2389
03:26:09,250 --> 03:26:15,194
[SPEAKER_22]: Okay, what are folks' thoughts on the boundaries for the BA1?

2390
03:26:15,314 --> 03:26:26,942
[SPEAKER_22]: Yep, I can.

2391
03:26:36,287 --> 03:26:40,170
[SPEAKER_22]: Yeah, it's probably worth putting it on screen Emily, just so people can get the graphic representation of it.

2392
03:26:40,770 --> 03:26:47,775
[SPEAKER_15]: Just one moment.

2393
03:26:52,278 --> 03:26:53,219
[SPEAKER_08]: Man, is that an old hand?

2394
03:26:55,180 --> 03:27:04,446
[SPEAKER_24]: Well, I mean, yeah, this was the two boundaries issues were the exact things that I was going to ask about, you know, request.

2395
03:27:06,602 --> 03:27:09,145
[SPEAKER_24]: Yeah, request to vote on those.

2396
03:27:09,405 --> 03:27:13,109
[SPEAKER_08]: Council said we're good with original boundaries on VA1.

2397
03:27:13,270 --> 03:27:17,675
[SPEAKER_08]: So if we have to come back and vote on it, but the city board is talking right now.

2398
03:27:22,777 --> 03:27:31,345
[SPEAKER_15]: So just to explain this, the red dashed lines here are the parcels that were proposed to be taken out.

2399
03:27:31,905 --> 03:27:36,770
[SPEAKER_15]: The green is the original boundaries.

2400
03:27:37,030 --> 03:27:43,236
[SPEAKER_15]: So it's just these areas, the red dashed lines that were proposed to be removed from the original boundary.

2401
03:27:44,560 --> 03:27:48,727
[SPEAKER_22]: So I'd like to just engage in this a little bit more.

2402
03:27:48,747 --> 03:27:54,457
[SPEAKER_22]: I've actually done a little bit of more, based on the conversation we had at the last meeting.

2403
03:27:55,770 --> 03:28:20,558
[SPEAKER_22]: I actually spoke to a real estate person evaluating those properties, and this is a person I've known for many years, and she didn't think there was an economic way to really develop those to a four-story height, given that every one of those buildings is worth at least a million dollars, and some of them are condoized, which you mentioned at the last meeting.

2404
03:28:21,198 --> 03:28:27,581
[SPEAKER_22]: which I think is why you referred to them as probably not a short-term development potential.

2405
03:28:27,721 --> 03:28:30,343
[SPEAKER_22]: I don't know if that's the exact term, but that's what you meant.

2406
03:28:31,643 --> 03:28:38,867
[SPEAKER_22]: So I personally have actually changed my mind on this because I actually don't think it's going to happen.

2407
03:28:39,507 --> 03:28:49,893
[SPEAKER_22]: I think we're zoning something for something that will probably not happen in at least 20 years, if ever, because to assemble five or six of those properties at over a million dollars

2408
03:28:50,493 --> 03:28:55,860
[SPEAKER_22]: tear them down, build a four-story building with parking, you're not going to make a dime.

2409
03:28:56,220 --> 03:28:59,604
[SPEAKER_22]: I just don't see it happening for almost every single one of those properties.

2410
03:29:00,305 --> 03:29:10,037
[SPEAKER_22]: So I guess my opposition, which I had in the previous meetings, was largely about the character of the neighborhood, but I just don't think it's going to happen because the numbers in my

2411
03:29:10,697 --> 03:29:19,584
[SPEAKER_22]: The evaluation with a real estate person who crunches these numbers every single day, she just doesn't think it's going to happen in a long time.

2412
03:29:19,844 --> 03:29:20,965
[SPEAKER_22]: It's just economically.

2413
03:29:21,705 --> 03:29:30,672
[SPEAKER_22]: The other parts we talked about, because they're larger sites, because they're bigger lots, I think they're easier for the rest of the BA1, largely.

2414
03:29:31,452 --> 03:29:38,717
[SPEAKER_22]: But the area outlined in the red dash line, I just don't see those triple-deckers in many of those buildings changing for decades.

2415
03:29:41,118 --> 03:29:42,419
[SPEAKER_22]: evolved opinion, if you will.

2416
03:29:43,620 --> 03:29:50,207
[SPEAKER_22]: Anyway, I would reach out to the city board and see if they have any thoughts either way.

2417
03:29:58,635 --> 03:29:58,855
[SPEAKER_22]: Dina?

2418
03:30:02,985 --> 03:30:08,649
[SPEAKER_16]: I liked you for when you proposed the change in the boundaries.

2419
03:30:09,209 --> 03:30:09,869
[SPEAKER_16]: I was with you.

2420
03:30:09,930 --> 03:30:11,030
[SPEAKER_16]: I felt that was right.

2421
03:30:11,090 --> 03:30:22,978
[SPEAKER_16]: But after you just persuaded me, after looking into it a little bit deeper and speaking to real estate, I think I'm fine with keeping the boundaries as is.

2422
03:30:23,118 --> 03:30:24,519
[SPEAKER_16]: I will go along with that.

2423
03:30:24,539 --> 03:30:25,680
[SPEAKER_22]: Appreciate it.

2424
03:30:25,840 --> 03:30:29,662
[SPEAKER_22]: I wouldn't propose it if I thought the neighborhood would be damaged by it.

2425
03:30:29,782 --> 03:30:30,743
[SPEAKER_22]: I just don't think it will.

2426
03:30:33,543 --> 03:30:41,126
[SPEAKER_16]: I think your logic is compelling, and I think that sounds fine to me.

2427
03:30:41,647 --> 03:30:44,868
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you, Dina.

2428
03:30:44,948 --> 03:30:46,029
[SPEAKER_22]: Paige, would you like to go next?

2429
03:30:46,049 --> 03:30:49,690
[SPEAKER_10]: I agree.

2430
03:30:49,870 --> 03:30:53,072
[SPEAKER_10]: And thank you, Doug, for explaining that, because you explained it before, and I appreciate that.

2431
03:30:53,332 --> 03:30:53,752
[SPEAKER_10]: So agreed.

2432
03:30:53,772 --> 03:30:57,173
[SPEAKER_22]: OK.

2433
03:30:57,914 --> 03:30:58,374
[SPEAKER_22]: Ali.

2434
03:30:59,635 --> 03:31:00,415
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm fine with that.

2435
03:31:01,535 --> 03:31:02,696
[SPEAKER_22]: You're fine with the original boundaries?

2436
03:31:03,307 --> 03:31:03,487
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

2437
03:31:04,287 --> 03:31:04,607
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you.

2438
03:31:07,148 --> 03:31:07,588
[SPEAKER_22]: And Sean?

2439
03:31:10,508 --> 03:31:13,489
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, I'm fine with the lower heights.

2440
03:31:13,709 --> 03:31:20,290
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm fine with the original boundaries because I don't think the heights are going to be at any point in the future much higher than what's there now.

2441
03:31:20,570 --> 03:31:20,871
[SPEAKER_22]: Okay.

2442
03:31:21,091 --> 03:31:21,611
[SPEAKER_22]: Thank you, Sean.

2443
03:31:22,591 --> 03:31:22,791
[SPEAKER_22]: So.

2444
03:31:22,811 --> 03:31:23,691
[SPEAKER_22]: I think we're good.

2445
03:31:23,771 --> 03:31:24,251
[SPEAKER_22]: I think we're good.

2446
03:31:24,531 --> 03:31:24,671
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

2447
03:31:25,371 --> 03:31:26,012
[SPEAKER_08]: Boundaries done.

2448
03:31:27,632 --> 03:31:28,172
[SPEAKER_22]: Do we need a motion?

2449
03:31:28,752 --> 03:31:30,472
[SPEAKER_08]: No, I don't think we, I think we're not changing anything.

2450
03:31:34,816 --> 03:31:41,901
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, I think that leaves us with the purpose-built student housing as the last kind of big thing on the plate.

2451
03:31:46,084 --> 03:31:47,165
[SPEAKER_08]: You guys talked about it, what?

2452
03:31:48,165 --> 03:31:49,707
[SPEAKER_08]: You guys talked about it a lot last night.

2453
03:31:49,887 --> 03:31:52,288
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know if you have opinions.

2454
03:31:52,809 --> 03:31:55,110
[SPEAKER_08]: We took overview at the presentation tonight.

2455
03:31:55,130 --> 03:31:56,251
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know if we want to start.

2456
03:31:56,772 --> 03:31:57,732
[SPEAKER_08]: I think we could go either way.

2457
03:31:57,752 --> 03:32:02,215
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know if, yeah.

2458
03:32:02,996 --> 03:32:04,397
[SPEAKER_08]: We can start with the CD board it looks like.

2459
03:32:06,998 --> 03:32:14,362
[SPEAKER_22]: Maybe, Sean, you're the one who actually drafted the original language and did a lot of the wordsmithing and editing.

2460
03:32:14,402 --> 03:32:16,463
[SPEAKER_22]: Maybe you could take the lead on this one.

2461
03:32:22,744 --> 03:32:31,530
[SPEAKER_04]: So again, Alicia did a very nice job of kind of setting out what this use is and what it's intended to be at the beginning of the meeting.

2462
03:32:31,770 --> 03:32:46,099
[SPEAKER_04]: But just to recap, so essentially this is, you could think of it as a dormitory, but a privately owned tax generating building for students with some exceptions.

2463
03:32:46,380 --> 03:32:51,103
[SPEAKER_04]: And what we're trying to do in regards to the students is make

2464
03:32:52,099 --> 03:32:58,544
[SPEAKER_04]: limit that mostly to students who are enrolled in a college in Medford or Somerville.

2465
03:32:59,265 --> 03:33:01,927
[SPEAKER_04]: There's only one college I know of in Medford or Somerville.

2466
03:33:01,967 --> 03:33:21,283
[SPEAKER_04]: So essentially it would be we're trying to get tough students out of the neighborhoods, free up some of the two and three family houses that they're now occupying and get them into a larger, more traditional type dormitory setting.

2467
03:33:22,613 --> 03:33:38,244
[SPEAKER_04]: We did build in a number of safeguards and I think those will be useful for the Community Development Board when they're evaluating, you know, if a proposal comes forward on this use, those will be helpful and they'll be helpful going forward.

2468
03:33:39,765 --> 03:33:46,089
[SPEAKER_04]: One of the things that I wanted to add either into the

2469
03:33:47,380 --> 03:34:01,486
[SPEAKER_04]: probably into the definition perhaps, was just I think that there should be an allowed retail use on the first floor of these buildings in the event that the developer wanted to put in a cafe or put in some retail use.

2470
03:34:01,526 --> 03:34:04,488
[SPEAKER_04]: That might be nice both for the residents and for the neighborhood.

2471
03:34:04,588 --> 03:34:12,691
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think that should be included without, because this is not a mixed use development.

2472
03:34:12,771 --> 03:34:14,992
[SPEAKER_04]: It's its own purpose built housing.

2473
03:34:15,052 --> 03:34:16,013
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think we would need

2474
03:34:17,213 --> 03:34:22,375
[SPEAKER_04]: And Emily can correct me if I'm wrong, but I think we should make some specific allowance.

2475
03:34:22,756 --> 03:34:23,236
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, she left.

2476
03:34:25,657 --> 03:34:26,958
[SPEAKER_04]: Paula can correct me if I'm wrong.

2477
03:34:29,539 --> 03:34:36,322
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think we should make some specific allocation for retail use.

2478
03:34:38,263 --> 03:34:40,724
[SPEAKER_04]: And then Alicia had mentioned

2479
03:34:42,330 --> 03:34:50,935
[SPEAKER_04]: that if they lost the use, that they'd be subject to all the zoning ordinances, including inclusionary housing.

2480
03:34:50,975 --> 03:35:06,583
[SPEAKER_04]: But I don't think we have in here that they're excluded from inclusionary housing, which we should probably mention, and which may also exclude them from some incentives for the affordable housing incentives as well.

2481
03:35:08,164 --> 03:35:10,485
[SPEAKER_04]: So they'd have to go look at other incentives.

2482
03:35:12,040 --> 03:35:14,161
[SPEAKER_11]: So we were just sort of discussing that.

2483
03:35:14,821 --> 03:35:19,203
[SPEAKER_11]: Sorry that we have been back chattering but we're trying to be as efficient with your time as possible.

2484
03:35:19,223 --> 03:35:21,144
[SPEAKER_11]: We're going to work some things out over here.

2485
03:35:21,164 --> 03:35:21,204
[SPEAKER_11]: So.

2486
03:35:24,527 --> 03:35:33,130
[SPEAKER_11]: I firmly believe that they should not do inclusionary housing because in order to do inclusionary housing you have to be on the state list.

2487
03:35:33,490 --> 03:35:41,252
[SPEAKER_11]: To be on the state list you have to do a public lottery and you can have no restrictions about who is eligible to live there other than income.

2488
03:35:43,199 --> 03:35:53,147
[SPEAKER_11]: For Medford's inclusionary housing, you don't want randomly lotteried people in that are not students into these units.

2489
03:35:53,347 --> 03:35:54,768
[SPEAKER_11]: That would not be appropriate.

2490
03:35:55,249 --> 03:36:05,597
[SPEAKER_11]: So we, one, do think it needs to be exempted from inclusionary housing, with the caveat that if it ever became multifamily, it would absolutely have to do it.

2491
03:36:07,238 --> 03:36:09,400
[SPEAKER_11]: That means they cannot take that incentive.

2492
03:36:09,960 --> 03:36:13,683
[SPEAKER_11]: And it does mean that we were looking to see, well, what could they do?

2493
03:36:14,123 --> 03:36:16,625
[SPEAKER_11]: And we are, of course, looking at the BA3 area.

2494
03:36:17,085 --> 03:36:19,807
[SPEAKER_11]: That area, it's very easy for them to do.

2495
03:36:20,728 --> 03:36:26,312
[SPEAKER_11]: There's a half story for parking underneath and behind.

2496
03:36:26,452 --> 03:36:28,154
[SPEAKER_11]: That's very easy for them to get.

2497
03:36:28,814 --> 03:36:32,237
[SPEAKER_11]: We would expect any building there, frankly, to be doing that.

2498
03:36:33,297 --> 03:36:39,961
[SPEAKER_11]: The other thing is that we think a pocket park would be really appropriate because this is such a large parcel.

2499
03:36:40,401 --> 03:36:42,102
[SPEAKER_11]: So we think they would take that up on it.

2500
03:36:42,582 --> 03:36:49,405
[SPEAKER_11]: Some of the others are for putting some plaza area and seating like some amenities that's available to the public.

2501
03:36:49,886 --> 03:36:53,367
[SPEAKER_11]: So that also seems very reasonable for them to be putting in there.

2502
03:36:55,778 --> 03:37:13,082
[SPEAKER_11]: So those were sort of the other things that seemed reasonable is that the development provide a minimum of 50% of the ground floor rents, meaning commercial rents, at no less than 15% below market for a minimum tenancy of three years for non-residential tenants.

2503
03:37:14,062 --> 03:37:21,303
[SPEAKER_11]: So basically we also think giving discounted rents to the commercial or non-profits is also something they could take up on that.

2504
03:37:21,643 --> 03:37:24,044
[SPEAKER_11]: So we do see that there are a bunch of options there.

2505
03:37:24,604 --> 03:37:28,269
[SPEAKER_11]: that a project like that could take up.

2506
03:37:29,010 --> 03:37:37,460
[SPEAKER_11]: I believe that one of the reasons for wanting to do this, the student housing, would be because they would save money on not having to do affordable housing.

2507
03:37:39,629 --> 03:37:53,077
[SPEAKER_11]: We have had the tough storm as part of their agreement with the city of Medford provided a payment to the affordable housing trust sort of in lieu because obviously they would never do affordable housing in a tough storm.

2508
03:37:54,378 --> 03:38:01,262
[SPEAKER_11]: So we haven't talked about anything like that but requiring some sort of payment to the trust is not a crazy idea.

2509
03:38:01,962 --> 03:38:06,324
[SPEAKER_11]: We would definitely need some time to do math to figure out what would be an appropriate number.

2510
03:38:07,485 --> 03:38:10,886
[SPEAKER_11]: Or you could just say, we actually need the student housing, so let's not worry about that.

2511
03:38:10,926 --> 03:38:14,728
[SPEAKER_11]: If it ever becomes an apartment building, then they have public housing.

2512
03:38:15,248 --> 03:38:17,289
[SPEAKER_11]: So I think I answered even more than your question.

2513
03:38:17,349 --> 03:38:21,551
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, yeah, no, that was great.

2514
03:38:21,731 --> 03:38:24,312
[SPEAKER_04]: I didn't have anything else, Doug.

2515
03:38:25,053 --> 03:38:25,253
Okay.

2516
03:38:27,011 --> 03:38:27,451
[SPEAKER_06]: Questions?

2517
03:38:27,832 --> 03:38:28,953
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

2518
03:38:30,254 --> 03:38:36,799
[SPEAKER_08]: Do we have questions from city councillors at this time on the proposed purpose built student housing use?

2519
03:38:40,782 --> 03:38:40,962
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah.

2520
03:38:43,004 --> 03:38:44,105
[SPEAKER_08]: Or thoughts or comments?

2521
03:38:44,865 --> 03:38:45,726
[SPEAKER_08]: Do we have a motion?

2522
03:38:50,850 --> 03:38:51,631
[SPEAKER_08]: Councillor Scarpelli.

2523
03:38:53,637 --> 03:39:21,800
[SPEAKER_27]: I think that, like I said earlier, the work last night by the Community Development Board and our team, I think that eliminating what we can eliminate and what we can control, I think we put in some safeguards that I thought that adding those in, the review every year and making sure they're in compliance, I think that

2524
03:39:22,923 --> 03:39:32,229
[SPEAKER_27]: really prepares the process to have oversight.

2525
03:39:32,289 --> 03:39:49,478
[SPEAKER_27]: And I think that that's key but I think that the biggest question is as we move forward with this process, there might be more that we can add to these processes, these mandates.

2526
03:39:52,845 --> 03:39:56,788
[SPEAKER_27]: Would that end tonight or could we have option to keep, to look into that?

2527
03:39:58,489 --> 03:40:21,987
[SPEAKER_27]: Like I know I said that, you know, I know that although the gentleman from Tufts came up and said that Tufts doesn't like it but it's going to happen so maybe as part of the management process, understanding the process and policies of what Tufts mandates and or Harvard mandates that part of the management plan, whatever is required by,

2528
03:40:22,693 --> 03:40:36,564
[SPEAKER_27]: the management team that the more stringent rule applies but still has to fulfill what each individual academic institution that they represent that comes in.

2529
03:40:36,644 --> 03:40:50,415
[SPEAKER_27]: So I think that's my process right now is understanding if we can really do more as we go along because I think that what we heard is great but there's also,

2530
03:40:51,215 --> 03:41:02,920
[SPEAKER_27]: You know, keeping, that's why keeping the public portion open until maybe going through the incentive process gives us that ability.

2531
03:41:03,521 --> 03:41:12,304
[SPEAKER_27]: But that was my two cents, Mr. Beers, and it's getting late, Council President, so I'm starting to ramble.

2532
03:41:13,465 --> 03:41:17,807
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, it sounded like,

2533
03:41:19,380 --> 03:41:31,047
[SPEAKER_08]: want to give some direction to PDS and the zoning consultants around maybe adding some additional requirements on the management plan?

2534
03:41:50,886 --> 03:42:01,915
[SPEAKER_27]: We were here till midnight last night.

2535
03:42:04,797 --> 03:42:05,077
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

2536
03:42:05,298 --> 03:42:08,420
[SPEAKER_08]: Sounds like take a little more time is what Councilor Scarpelli is saying.

2537
03:42:08,440 --> 03:42:10,522
[SPEAKER_08]: Do we have other comments from members of the council?

2538
03:42:10,542 --> 03:42:15,325
[SPEAKER_08]: Take a little more time with the management plan.

2539
03:42:15,606 --> 03:42:15,826
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

2540
03:42:18,878 --> 03:42:20,699
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Callahan, Councilor Millan, Councilor Lemming.

2541
03:42:23,220 --> 03:42:26,201
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Lemming.

2542
03:42:27,501 --> 03:42:45,868
[SPEAKER_24]: So the motion to move forward with this would just be to include the definition for, sorry, it's really late for me, for a purpose built housing into the use tables.

2543
03:42:48,553 --> 03:42:56,178
[SPEAKER_08]: Yep and it sounded like Councillor Scarpelli wants to continue to discuss the management plan as well or like see if there's additional conditions for the management plan.

2544
03:42:57,299 --> 03:42:57,559
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

2545
03:42:58,980 --> 03:43:01,102
[SPEAKER_08]: Any further discussion Councillor Kelly and Councillor Malayne.

2546
03:43:10,405 --> 03:43:18,312
[SPEAKER_32]: I felt like the Community Development Board had put together a pretty robust plan on it in the discussion of what they pulled together.

2547
03:43:18,412 --> 03:43:28,039
[SPEAKER_32]: So I don't know what more else that would need to be discussed because it sounded like you already had put a lot of thought and effort into it.

2548
03:43:28,720 --> 03:43:31,462
[SPEAKER_32]: So unless I'm missing something, I don't know.

2549
03:43:31,482 --> 03:43:34,805
[SPEAKER_32]: That's what it sounded like to me when Sean ran through it.

2550
03:43:34,825 --> 03:43:35,165
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, okay.

2551
03:43:35,205 --> 03:43:39,028
