04:01:17,474 --> 04:01:21,414
[SPEAKER_27]: I can, I thank you, Mr. President, through you to the Chair.

2720
04:01:21,434 --> 04:01:26,715
[SPEAKER_27]: I can appreciate that, but I just want us to look at history.

2721
04:01:28,776 --> 04:01:38,638
[SPEAKER_27]: The last time we looked at something that really wasn't truly a big deal where we left the public comment open,

2722
04:01:40,265 --> 04:01:41,726
[SPEAKER_27]: it became really bigger than it was.

2723
04:01:41,966 --> 04:01:46,129
[SPEAKER_27]: And I think that this isn't, this isn't, this is low hanging fruit.

2724
04:01:46,149 --> 04:01:48,530
[SPEAKER_27]: I don't think this is a big deal if we kept it open.

2725
04:01:49,390 --> 04:02:05,000
[SPEAKER_27]: If anything, if finding an end date may be asked to keep it open until our August meeting where it gives the finality so people are secure in the date in August, our meeting in August.

2726
04:02:05,835 --> 04:02:19,686
[SPEAKER_27]: That if there's anything in between there, we can look to see if it's something substantial that we all agree with, that we can add on to when our consultants can work on it before the CD board gets their finality.

2727
04:02:20,246 --> 04:02:25,470
[SPEAKER_27]: And I don't think this is a deal breaker.

2728
04:02:25,490 --> 04:02:34,217
[SPEAKER_27]: I just think that this could be something that when it's all said and done, we've done everything in our power to listen to everybody

2729
04:02:35,282 --> 04:02:40,685
[SPEAKER_27]: People that have fatigue that are waiting, waiting another few weeks isn't a big deal, I don't think.

2730
04:02:40,805 --> 04:02:48,210
[SPEAKER_27]: It's the people that are finding out now that really don't think at this minute, and I've had a few messages that

2731
04:02:49,483 --> 04:02:52,005
[SPEAKER_27]: Understanding this process tonight, we did a lot tonight.

2732
04:02:52,465 --> 04:02:55,988
[SPEAKER_27]: So understanding this process now and saying, okay, now I get it.

2733
04:02:56,168 --> 04:02:58,649
[SPEAKER_27]: Now this, I feel comfortable with this.

2734
04:02:58,710 --> 04:02:59,310
[SPEAKER_27]: I feel comfortable.

2735
04:02:59,330 --> 04:03:01,952
[SPEAKER_27]: Can you give me an explanation about this point?

2736
04:03:02,432 --> 04:03:03,693
[SPEAKER_27]: And that's probably it.

2737
04:03:04,273 --> 04:03:07,636
[SPEAKER_27]: It's something a lot that I think we can handle as a council.

2738
04:03:08,873 --> 04:03:13,055
[SPEAKER_27]: So again, that's my prerogative.

2739
04:03:13,215 --> 04:03:18,737
[SPEAKER_27]: I think that this is why we have an elected body that we can vote and that's what the process is.

2740
04:03:18,777 --> 04:03:27,540
[SPEAKER_27]: But I don't, like I said, I think that keeping it open just offers that last person that needs to feel that they're being listened to.

2741
04:03:29,707 --> 04:03:32,630
[SPEAKER_27]: I just caution you to remember back on Salem Street.

2742
04:03:33,231 --> 04:03:35,253
[SPEAKER_27]: That was the biggest issue with the end there.

2743
04:03:35,333 --> 04:03:38,696
[SPEAKER_27]: So I'm beating a dead horse so I move on.

2744
04:03:38,776 --> 04:03:39,537
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you Mr. President.

2745
04:03:40,838 --> 04:03:41,318
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

2746
04:03:41,339 --> 04:03:43,861
[SPEAKER_08]: I do have Councilor Lemming.

2747
04:03:43,881 --> 04:03:46,063
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know if Director Hunt you wanted to add something.

2748
04:03:47,024 --> 04:03:48,766
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm going to let you all finish.

2749
04:03:48,846 --> 04:03:49,887
[SPEAKER_11]: We figured out dates.

2750
04:03:50,407 --> 04:03:50,648
[SPEAKER_08]: Great.

2751
04:03:51,028 --> 04:03:51,248
[SPEAKER_08]: All right.

2752
04:03:51,428 --> 04:03:51,969
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Lemming.

2753
04:03:55,578 --> 04:03:56,619
[SPEAKER_24]: I do appreciate that.

2754
04:03:56,759 --> 04:04:05,848
[SPEAKER_24]: I will say that, so we heard some comparisons with Medford Square earlier in the meeting in terms of this process.

2755
04:04:06,008 --> 04:04:12,154
[SPEAKER_24]: And all things considered, there was some contention there, but that process went pretty smoothly.

2756
04:04:12,214 --> 04:04:14,096
[SPEAKER_24]: We did have, and we had,

2757
04:04:19,301 --> 04:04:22,363
[SPEAKER_24]: joint hearings that were one month apart.

2758
04:04:23,463 --> 04:04:35,469
[SPEAKER_24]: We had a couple of those and there was quite a bit of time in Ennis' contract then to do that.

2759
04:04:35,729 --> 04:04:41,052
[SPEAKER_24]: I think what we discussed with this with Boston Avenue was,

2760
04:04:44,092 --> 04:04:56,264
[SPEAKER_24]: I don't I don't think it's necessary that it take quite as much time as Medford square one because we have had about as many meetings just a shorter time in between in between the two of them.

2761
04:04:56,285 --> 04:04:56,345
[SPEAKER_24]: But.

2762
04:05:00,127 --> 04:05:10,640
[SPEAKER_24]: But also because we've incorporated a lot of the lessons from Medford square a lot of the fixes that we put into Medford square things are broken with the zoning we were able to incorporate in Boston Avenue.

2763
04:05:11,121 --> 04:05:19,090
[SPEAKER_24]: So it was, so we are able, so I feel like we've gotten to that point where we can sort of where we've sort of streamline the process and.

2764
04:05:20,224 --> 04:05:35,571
[SPEAKER_24]: Again, what we've been we put out we put out schedules we put out messaging to the public that we would have sort of a final product by by June 30, and you know, to me, to me deadlines are pretty important.

2765
04:05:37,197 --> 04:05:53,853
[SPEAKER_24]: I think that, you know, I totally respect what my colleagues saying, but I also think that if we keep the public hearing open, then given that Boston, you know, Boston Avenue is, it's an area that we're, you know, it's fairly dense, a lot of residents live around there.

2766
04:05:54,754 --> 04:06:00,699
[SPEAKER_24]: You know, we're gonna have, we will have, anytime we have a new meeting, a new public hearing, there's going to be,

2767
04:06:02,162 --> 04:06:08,758
[SPEAKER_24]: new residents who maybe have never heard about the zoning process at all and it's the first time they're hearing about it.

2768
04:06:09,119 --> 04:06:10,021
[SPEAKER_24]: And I think that's just

2769
04:06:11,598 --> 04:06:14,861
[SPEAKER_24]: I think I think that that's that's just what happens any time.

2770
04:06:14,941 --> 04:06:20,646
[SPEAKER_24]: Any time you have a new meeting, there's always going to be folks who, you know, maybe it's their first time hearing about it.

2771
04:06:20,726 --> 04:06:33,336
[SPEAKER_24]: But I think overall, keeping with deadlines and keeping with a schedule on the whole incorporates more faith into the process and tells people that, yes, this is moving along.

2772
04:06:33,537 --> 04:06:36,239
[SPEAKER_24]: And it's it's important for messaging as I see it.

2773
04:06:40,894 --> 04:06:42,599
[SPEAKER_08]: Too many further comment by members of the council.

2774
04:06:47,474 --> 04:06:48,397
[SPEAKER_08]: Councilor Malauulu.

2775
04:06:50,376 --> 04:06:51,777
[SPEAKER_32]: Sorry, I keep jumping ahead.

2776
04:06:51,797 --> 04:06:53,579
[SPEAKER_32]: No, that's great.

2777
04:06:53,599 --> 04:06:53,879
[SPEAKER_32]: Sorry.

2778
04:06:54,699 --> 04:07:13,593
[SPEAKER_32]: I guess I just wanted to ask, I kind of did it on the side here to George, but Councilor Scarpelli, but even if we close public, quote unquote public hearing, people can still send in comments and then we can still read through and see and be able to get that information as well.

2779
04:07:13,833 --> 04:07:17,376
[SPEAKER_32]: Is that, I'm just, people can still send stuff in to us as well.

2780
04:07:17,927 --> 04:07:21,502
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm seeing someone saying no to me from the audience.

2781
04:07:24,841 --> 04:07:27,562
[SPEAKER_32]: I mean, people can send stuff in, but it's closed as a public.

2782
04:07:27,582 --> 04:07:28,662
[SPEAKER_08]: I think it depends on what counts.

2783
04:07:28,722 --> 04:07:39,966
[SPEAKER_08]: I think it's like, if you close the public hearing, then the comments that people receive are not legally part of the zoning amendment record, but we can have public comment at any meeting that we choose to have.

2784
04:07:40,206 --> 04:07:40,486
[SPEAKER_32]: Okay.

2785
04:07:40,766 --> 04:07:43,767
[SPEAKER_08]: So I think it's yes and no.

2786
04:07:44,287 --> 04:07:44,587
[SPEAKER_08]: Got it.

2787
04:07:45,187 --> 04:07:46,167
[SPEAKER_32]: All right.

2788
04:07:46,728 --> 04:07:47,128
[SPEAKER_32]: Fair enough.

2789
04:07:47,448 --> 04:07:47,768
[SPEAKER_32]: Thank you.

2790
04:07:49,075 --> 04:07:59,683
[SPEAKER_08]: We would be saying we've made the major decisions and we're closing the record on the major decisions, but it doesn't mean that at a future meeting we cannot open the floor to public comment and feedback, right?

2791
04:08:00,344 --> 04:08:06,929
[SPEAKER_08]: It's like a 40A thing and then a meeting council or CDB rules thing.

2792
04:08:07,570 --> 04:08:08,250
[SPEAKER_08]: Two pieces there.

2793
04:08:12,674 --> 04:08:16,737
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, I have an opinion, as I usually do.

2794
04:08:20,378 --> 04:08:29,662
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, I mean, personally, I tend to side with Councilor Lemming and Councilor Malauulu here.

2795
04:08:33,544 --> 04:08:36,406
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't think closing the public hearing means we don't hear anymore from the public.

2796
04:08:36,606 --> 04:08:41,148
[SPEAKER_08]: I just think it means it's a signal to the public that we have consensus on the major elements of the zoning.

2797
04:08:42,609 --> 04:08:43,169
[SPEAKER_08]: I would feel

2798
04:08:44,408 --> 04:08:46,069
[SPEAKER_08]: more comfortable if we both did that.

2799
04:08:46,209 --> 04:09:04,176
[SPEAKER_08]: I think if the CD board wants to keep the public hearing open to an August or a September meeting, and kind of wants to figure out how that relates to the mayor's, you know, condition that we don't have meetings in the summer, I'm open to that.

2800
04:09:04,476 --> 04:09:11,759
[SPEAKER_08]: I think if we all agree tonight that we've reached consensus on the major decisions, but you guys want to keep the public hearing open,

2801
04:09:13,892 --> 04:09:15,293
[SPEAKER_08]: I think we would close ours.

2802
04:09:15,433 --> 04:09:23,398
[SPEAKER_08]: You could keep yours open, send your recommendations to us, and then we will consider those recommendations when they come back at a council meeting.

2803
04:09:24,178 --> 04:09:28,241
[SPEAKER_08]: Probably it sounds like it would be a September council meeting at that point.

2804
04:09:29,862 --> 04:09:30,922
[SPEAKER_08]: The 15th, I think.

2805
04:09:35,065 --> 04:09:36,626
[SPEAKER_08]: But it sounded like Alicia has dates.

2806
04:09:36,886 --> 04:09:38,427
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know what the proposals are there.

2807
04:09:41,686 --> 04:09:50,489
[SPEAKER_22]: Before you do that, Alicia, if you don't mind, I'd like to actually ask the CD board if they want to close the public hearing tonight or leave it open.

2808
04:09:51,510 --> 04:10:01,213
[SPEAKER_22]: And then you can, Alicia can, I think you probably have option A and B with dates, but depending on which avenue we choose, go ahead, Paige.

2809
04:10:01,733 --> 04:10:01,913
[SPEAKER_10]: Sure.

2810
04:10:02,173 --> 04:10:03,294
[SPEAKER_10]: I would like to keep it open, please.

2811
04:10:03,934 --> 04:10:04,294
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

2812
04:10:07,775 --> 04:10:09,616
[SPEAKER_22]: Sean, do you have a thought?

2813
04:10:11,680 --> 04:10:28,605
[SPEAKER_04]: Fine closing the public hearing at this point with the caveat that President Beard had mentioned earlier that he wouldn't move to pass any zoning or vote on any zoning at the city council level until we send him our final draft.

2814
04:10:29,826 --> 04:10:31,746
[SPEAKER_22]: Which we'll talk about dates in a second.

2815
04:10:33,347 --> 04:10:36,808
[SPEAKER_22]: Ari, do you have any thoughts on hearing open or closed?

2816
04:10:38,528 --> 04:10:42,010
[SPEAKER_20]: I see arguments in both sides.

2817
04:10:42,630 --> 04:10:52,875
[SPEAKER_20]: I think that there is a practical benefit to making it clear that the major decisions have been made.

2818
04:10:53,275 --> 04:11:04,900
[SPEAKER_20]: I also have been very clear throughout this process that it is incredibly important to me that the public have a full iterative cycle on each major zoning, that they see a concrete plan

2819
04:11:06,850 --> 04:11:08,872
[SPEAKER_20]: get to provide feedback and we go back again.

2820
04:11:09,132 --> 04:11:15,138
[SPEAKER_20]: So I think actually to me a reasonable compromise feels like city council closes, we leave it open.

2821
04:11:16,539 --> 04:11:19,802
[SPEAKER_20]: And I think that gets us the benefits of both.

2822
04:11:20,282 --> 04:11:25,587
[SPEAKER_20]: And I don't want to belabor this discussion indefinitely given that it's 10 p.m.

2823
04:11:25,947 --> 04:11:31,112
[SPEAKER_20]: and that all of them lead to the same practical conclusions and it's entirely just what we call it.

2824
04:11:33,603 --> 04:11:37,325
[SPEAKER_22]: And Dina, any thoughts on open versus closed meeting for us?

2825
04:11:37,465 --> 04:11:38,886
[SPEAKER_22]: Not, sorry.

2826
04:11:41,628 --> 04:11:42,889
[SPEAKER_16]: I could go either way.

2827
04:11:43,009 --> 04:11:46,551
[SPEAKER_16]: I am, you know, I'm more Sean Began.

2828
04:11:46,651 --> 04:12:01,080
[SPEAKER_16]: I would feel fine with closing as long as we can continue to receive off the record comments and that we get confirmation from the city council that they will not do anything with our recommendations.

2829
04:12:02,137 --> 04:12:02,638
[SPEAKER_22]: Understood.

2830
04:12:04,159 --> 04:12:14,349
[SPEAKER_22]: My personal hesitation is because when we finished Medford Square, we actually had a plan.

2831
04:12:14,669 --> 04:12:25,138
[SPEAKER_22]: We'd had all the pieces written, clear, in writing, going into that last meeting, and we just don't have that now.

2832
04:12:27,901 --> 04:12:41,711
[SPEAKER_22]: I really hesitate to close off an avenue for public discussion for people who may have no, haven't been following this because they've been, you know, finishing up school, trying to deal with the high school.

2833
04:12:41,731 --> 04:12:50,257
[SPEAKER_22]: There's been so much going on this month that it's been almost impossible for us to even schedule meetings together and separately.

2834
04:12:50,397 --> 04:12:53,800
[SPEAKER_22]: So I tend to want to keep it open just on our side.

2835
04:12:53,820 --> 04:12:55,661
[SPEAKER_22]: I think you guys should close it if you're feeling comfortable.

2836
04:12:59,385 --> 04:13:06,573
[SPEAKER_16]: I just wanted to say I'd love to hear the date.

2837
04:13:07,174 --> 04:13:11,579
[SPEAKER_16]: And I would be more than willing to work over July to get it done.

2838
04:13:12,159 --> 04:13:14,101
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm just going to quickly come back to the council.

2839
04:13:14,322 --> 04:13:16,144
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm going to go to Councilor Callahan.

2840
04:13:17,604 --> 04:13:33,239
[SPEAKER_29]: Yeah, I just wanted to super quick mention that the one real effect that I think it has to open or not or to close or not close the public meeting is on any developers who may be considering working on a project.

2841
04:13:33,359 --> 04:13:38,484
[SPEAKER_29]: And we do have one that we know about that is considering working on a project.

2842
04:13:38,524 --> 04:13:40,706
[SPEAKER_29]: And I think without closing the hearing,

2843
04:13:41,306 --> 04:13:45,227
[SPEAKER_29]: They can't really feel sure that there is any consensus.

2844
04:13:46,728 --> 04:13:53,250
[SPEAKER_29]: It just means that it is technically up in the air and they cannot move forward.

2845
04:13:53,510 --> 04:13:56,570
[SPEAKER_29]: So, you know, that's a consideration, I think.

2846
04:13:56,590 --> 04:14:00,332
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Councilor Callahan.

2847
04:14:00,512 --> 04:14:02,372
[SPEAKER_08]: Director Hunt, you want to talk about the dates?

2848
04:14:04,253 --> 04:14:04,833
[SPEAKER_08]: Alicia?

2849
04:14:07,726 --> 04:14:11,127
[SPEAKER_11]: Sorry, I try to have things worked out before we put them in front of you.

2850
04:14:12,787 --> 04:14:26,051
[SPEAKER_11]: So here's what I think we just were discussing, is that we think that it would be useful for the board to have two working sessions in the summer, and the first one should not be too soon.

2851
04:14:27,171 --> 04:14:29,072
[SPEAKER_11]: And so we were proposing July 29th.

2852
04:14:29,632 --> 04:14:35,214
[SPEAKER_11]: I'm just across the board sticking to Wednesdays for consistency.

2853
04:14:37,294 --> 04:14:47,118
[SPEAKER_11]: So that's what we were considering would be the first working session for this, which is when we would all come back hopefully with worked out stuff.

2854
04:14:48,058 --> 04:14:52,520
[SPEAKER_11]: And then potentially we'd ask people if they're available to hold maybe August 19th.

2855
04:14:54,360 --> 04:15:00,582
[SPEAKER_11]: That would normally be a regular CD board meeting date, because we do the first and the thirds.

2856
04:15:01,242 --> 04:15:05,364
[SPEAKER_11]: And then if we needed, if things got completely worked out the 29th, great.

2857
04:15:05,444 --> 04:15:08,225
[SPEAKER_11]: And if not, then that's another session to come back to.

2858
04:15:09,225 --> 04:15:28,312
[SPEAKER_11]: and actually continue the public hearing if you're choosing to continue it on the CD board side to September 2nd because that sort of sticks to that plan of that's when there would be something by then, by a week before then at least for the public to look at, to be able to comment at.

2859
04:15:28,652 --> 04:15:36,455
[SPEAKER_11]: It's actually robustly long enough from now that we'd feel good about saying we could put something out real for the public September 2nd.

2860
04:15:37,275 --> 04:16:00,740
[SPEAKER_11]: the CD board could in fact have a real meeting, get public input that week, perhaps vote out a final version at that night, and then that's far enough in advance of, I think I heard that the city council's first September meeting is September 15th, then they could actually receive the recommendations on September 15th.

2861
04:16:02,620 --> 04:16:14,450
[SPEAKER_11]: It feels like it would work for us without stretching this all through the entire month of September and October, because I think the other option truly is to say, we kind of do nothing.

2862
04:16:16,071 --> 04:16:24,478
[SPEAKER_11]: Our next meeting on this topic at all will be September 2nd, and we'll start doing working sessions, and I don't really want to drag this out all fall.

2863
04:16:26,015 --> 04:16:30,116
[SPEAKER_22]: To clarify working sessions, is that everyone here or just the CD board?

2864
04:16:30,176 --> 04:16:33,537
[SPEAKER_11]: I think that it would be the CD board like we did last night.

2865
04:16:33,897 --> 04:16:36,757
[SPEAKER_11]: Like last night, the board was online.

2866
04:16:37,298 --> 04:16:39,038
[SPEAKER_11]: It was very collaborative.

2867
04:16:39,118 --> 04:16:40,538
[SPEAKER_11]: It wasn't everybody take your turn.

2868
04:16:40,558 --> 04:16:45,719
[SPEAKER_11]: It was like, let's have a conversation, like a group of people could have a conversation and work through something.

2869
04:16:46,640 --> 04:16:47,540
[SPEAKER_11]: It worked really well.

2870
04:16:47,680 --> 04:16:49,580
[SPEAKER_11]: It doesn't work when you have 14 people.

2871
04:16:49,780 --> 04:16:51,721
[SPEAKER_11]: It does work with five or six or seven.

2872
04:16:54,204 --> 04:16:59,849
[SPEAKER_11]: And that if for some reason you felt that people, so we'll continue to get public comment.

2873
04:16:59,889 --> 04:17:05,274
[SPEAKER_11]: We cannot prevent people from sending us messages, and you'd have those available to review.

2874
04:17:05,774 --> 04:17:14,302
[SPEAKER_11]: Whether or not you allowed people to speak during that meeting, you might say we wanna hear from the Tufts rapper, from the other student housing guy, I don't know.

2875
04:17:15,225 --> 04:17:26,828
[SPEAKER_22]: Can you clarify what date did you think, did you say that the final draft, plans, text, when would that be available to the public under this scenario?

2876
04:17:27,313 --> 04:17:31,477
[SPEAKER_11]: So the thought would be the public hearing would be September 2nd.

2877
04:17:31,637 --> 04:17:37,082
[SPEAKER_11]: And so I'm looking back sort of a week and saying you know by August 27th or 26.

2878
04:17:37,823 --> 04:17:42,267
[SPEAKER_11]: I mean so if we met the 19th it actually might be tight to get it the 27th.

2879
04:17:42,647 --> 04:17:45,510
[SPEAKER_11]: We might want to consider and we don't have to set this right now.

2880
04:17:45,870 --> 04:17:49,113
[SPEAKER_11]: Would August 12th be another like July 29th.

2881
04:17:50,234 --> 04:17:51,595
[SPEAKER_11]: Two weeks later is August 12th.

2882
04:17:54,071 --> 04:17:55,613
[SPEAKER_22]: Why do you think we need two sessions?

2883
04:17:55,633 --> 04:17:58,277
[SPEAKER_11]: And the 12th is your regular night.

2884
04:17:59,338 --> 04:18:01,041
[SPEAKER_11]: Maybe you just need one.

2885
04:18:01,982 --> 04:18:03,804
[SPEAKER_11]: I'd rather hold a date in my calendar.

2886
04:18:04,345 --> 04:18:05,487
[SPEAKER_22]: We have the dates, right?

2887
04:18:05,647 --> 04:18:07,249
[SPEAKER_22]: We have an August meeting anyway, right?

2888
04:18:07,807 --> 04:18:11,832
[SPEAKER_11]: So one of the things that I figured out is that I'm away a lot of your meeting dates.

2889
